{"title_page": "Gateshead International Stadium", "text_new": "{{featured article}}\n{{EngvarB|date=May 2014}}\n{{Infobox venue\n| stadium_name      = Gateshead International Stadium \n| logo_image        = \n| logo_caption      =\n| image             = [[File:Gateshead Stadium - geograph-1116309.jpg|250px|entrance]]\n| caption           = Main entrance to the stadium\n| fullname          = Gateshead International Stadium\n| former_names      = Gateshead Youth Stadium\n| location          = Neilson Road<br>[[Gateshead]]<br>[[Tyne and Wear]]<br>NE10 0EF\n| coordinates       = {{coord|54|57|40|N|1|34|47|W|display=inline,title}}\n| broke_ground      = 1955\n| built             = 1955\n| opened            = 27 August 1955\n| renovated         = 1974\n| expanded          = 2010\n| owner             = [[Gateshead Council#Local government|Gateshead Metropolitan Borough Council]]\n| operator          = Gateshead Metropolitan Borough Council\n| surface           = Synthetic running track, grass inner\n| scoreboard        = Yes &ndash; by HS Sports<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hssports.co.uk/displays-scoreboards/references?page=3|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151230111839/http://www.hssports.co.uk/displays-scoreboards/led-screen-scoreboard-references?page=3|archivedate=30 December 2015|title=HS Sports: references|publisher=HS Sports|year=2012|accessdate=9 November 2012}}</ref>\n| cost              = Originally \u00a330,000 (1955)<ref name=\"gateshead1\"/>\n| capacity          = 11,800\n| record_attendance = 14,797 (sports),<ref name=\"McGuirk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/sport/athletics-news/2009/08/27/gateshead-stadium-still-a-world-beater-venue-72703-24537934/|title=Gateshead Stadium still a world-beater venue|first=Bill|last=McGuirk|work=[[Newcastle Evening Chronicle]]|date=27 August 2009|accessdate=9 September 2012}}</ref> 30,000 (various concerts)\n| dimensions        = {{convert|100|x|64|m|yd|1}}\n| acreage           = 24.4 hectares\n| tenants           = [[Gateshead A.F.C.]] (1971-1973)<br>[[Gateshead United F.C.|Gateshead United]] (1974\u20131977)<br/>[[Gateshead F.C.]] (1977\u2013present)<br>[[Gateshead Harriers]] (1956&ndash;present)<br/>[[Gateshead Senators]] (1988&ndash;2012)<br/>[[Gateshead Thunder (1999)|Gateshead Thunder]] (1999)<br>[[Newcastle Thunder|Gateshead Thunder]] (2001&ndash;2014)\n|}}\n'''Gateshead International Stadium (GIS)''' is a [[multi-purpose stadium|multi-purpose]], [[all-seater]] venue in [[Gateshead]], Tyne and Wear, England. Originally known as the '''Gateshead Youth Stadium''', the venue was built in 1955 at a cost of \u00a330,000. It has since been extensively re-developed on three occasions. Its capacity of around 11,800{{refn|group=nb|This is the most widely quoted figure, but at least one council document provides a figure of 11,750.<ref name=\"Quinn\">{{cite web|url=http://online.gateshead.gov.uk/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-23427/Item+09+-+Delivery+of+the+Redevelopment+of+Gateshead+International+Stadium+report.doc |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140513235645/http://online.gateshead.gov.uk/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-23427/Item%2B09%2B-%2BDelivery%2Bof%2Bthe%2BRedevelopment%2Bof%2BGateshead%2BInternational%2BStadium%2Breport.doc |archivedate=13 May 2014 |title=Report to Cabinet &ndash; Delivery of the Redevelopment of Gateshead International Stadium |first=Derek |last=Quinn |publisher=Gateshead MBC |date=27 January 2009 |accessdate=28 December 2012 |url-status=dead }} at p.3</ref>}} is the greatest in the [[Metropolitan Borough of Gateshead]], the third-largest in Tyne and Wear (behind only [[St James' Park]] and the [[Stadium of Light]]) and the sixth-largest in [[North East England]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldstadiums.com/europe/countries/united_kingdom/england/north_east.shtml|title=Stadiums in North East England|publisher=World Stadiums|year=2012|accessdate=9 November 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120622114318/http://www.worldstadiums.com/europe/countries/united_kingdom/england/north_east.shtml|archivedate=22 June 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe main arena is principally used for athletics. The inaugural athletics competition at the redeveloped venue, the 1974 \"Gateshead Games\", was instigated by [[Brendan Foster]], a Gateshead Council employee at that time. By breaking the world record in the [[3000 metres|men's 3,000&nbsp;m]], Foster brought international publicity to the new stadium and began a tradition of athletics competitions at the venue, which has since hosted the [[British Grand Prix (athletics)|British Grand Prix]] (2003&ndash;10) and the [[European Team Championships]] in 1989, 2000 and 2013. It is the only venue to have hosted the latter event three times. Five world records have been set at the stadium, including two by [[pole vault]]er [[Yelena Isinbayeva]] and a tied [[100 metres]] record by [[Asafa Powell]] in 2006.\n\nAlthough the venue primarily caters for athletics, it is the current or former home to teams in several sports. It has been used by the town's main football club since 1971. Gateshead International Stadium was home to the [[Gateshead Thunder (1999)|Gateshead Thunder]] [[rugby league]] club during their spell in the [[Super League]] and the replacement [[Newcastle Thunder|Gateshead Thunder club]] played home games in the main arena, which was known as the '''Thunderdome''' when used by that team<ref>{{cite web|title=Gateshead Thunder end two-and-a-half-year wait for win|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/rugby-league/19422254|publisher=[[BBC|the BBC]]|date=30 August 2012|accessdate=18 January 2013}}</ref> until the club relocated to Newcastle in 2015. Gateshead Harriers Athletic Club, which includes Foster and [[Jonathan Edwards (triple jumper)|Jonathan Edwards]] among its life members, are the oldest tenants, having used the site since 1956. The stadium has also been used as a concert venue by numerous musical artists including [[Little Mix]], [[Guns N' Roses]], [[Bon Jovi]], [[Bryan Adams]] and [[Tina Turner]].\n\n==History and development==\n\nThe stadium is built on the site of two large chemical works opened in 1827 and 1834.<ref name=\"chroniclelive1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/communities/felling/2012/01/01/ten-interesting-facts-about-felling-72703-30939585/ |title=Ten interesting facts about Felling |work=[[Evening Chronicle|Newcastle Evening Chronicle]] |date=1 January 2012 |accessdate=28 August 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130202093036/http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/communities/felling/2012/01/01/ten-interesting-facts-about-felling-72703-30939585/ |archivedate=2 February 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>Lewis, 1848: 227</ref> These works initially thrived, but by the early part of the 20th century both were in terminal decline,<ref>Hewitt (part three), 1990: 1 at para. 5</ref> and were demolished in 1932 to leave behind a 2-million-tonne heap of spoil.<ref name=\"chroniclelive1\"/><ref name=\"DB8\">Report to Cabinet &ndash; Gateshead International Stadium &ndash; Draft Development Brief, 2010: 8</ref> This land, approximately {{convert|2|mi}} east of the centre of Gateshead,<ref>Report to Cabinet &ndash; Gateshead International Stadium &ndash; Draft Development Brief, 2010: 7</ref> was cleared in 1942 but continued to lie derelict until the mid-1950s.<ref name=\"DB8\"/>\n\nIn early 1955, Gateshead Council began work on transforming this land. The Gateshead Youth Stadium, built on the site of the old chemical works, was opened by [[Jim Peters (athlete)|Jim Peters]] on 27 August 1955.<ref name=\"gateshead1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gateshead2013.com/thevenue.html|title=The Venue &ndash; Gateshead International Stadium|publisher=Gateshead Council|year=2013|accessdate=19 January 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121215061336/http://www.gateshead2013.com/thevenue.html|archivedate=15 December 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Costing \u00a330,000, the original venue contained little more than a cinder running track and an asphalt cycling track, though floodlights and a seating area were added soon after.<ref name=\"gateshead1\"/> On 1&nbsp;July 1961, the arena hosted its first major competition\u2014the [[Vaux Breweries]] International Athletics Meet<ref name=\"BGR\">''The Brewing Grade Review'', 1961: 922</ref>\u2014but according to sportswriter John Gibson, the Youth Stadium remained \"little more than a minor track with a tiny grandstand and open terraces\".<ref name=\"ICN\">{{cite web|url=http://icnewcastle.icnetwork.co.uk/0200sport/0600athletics/tm_objectid=14208798%26method=full%26siteid=50081%26headline=face-to-face--brendan-foster-name_page.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151230110849/http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/sport/other-sport/face-to-face-brendan-foster-1615997|archivedate=30 December 2015|title=Face to Face: Brendan Foster|first=John|last=Gibson|work=[[Newcastle Evening Chronicle]]|date=4 May 2004|accessdate=28 December 2012}} at p.2</ref>\n\n[[File:Gateshead 1975.jpg|thumb|left|Aerial photograph of Gateshead (1975). The rebuilt stadium is prominent (top centre).]]According to author Thomas Telfer, by the turn of the 1970s, the town of Gateshead was suffering from \"the classic symptoms of decay in its inner-city areas\". The response during the 1960s had been a programme of systematic derelict land reclamation and environmental improvement.<ref>Telford, 1988: 79</ref> While these measures did not have an immediate positive impact on the perception of the town, Gateshead Council pressed ahead by looking to develop existing infrastructure with a view to overall regeneration.<ref>Telford, 1988: 80</ref> One such opportunity was identified at the Gateshead Youth Stadium, where the council believed that investment might raise the region's profile and bring international recognition.<ref>Moore, Fox and Elliot, 2003: 107</ref> In April 1974, Gateshead Council inaugurated a \"Sport and Recreation\" department.<ref name=\"ICN\"/> In July 1974, the council appointed [[Brendan Foster]]\u2014a former schoolteacher turned athlete and a native of [[Tyne and Wear]]\u2014as the Council's sport and recreation manager.<ref name=\"Gibson 2004:1\"/><ref name=\"Freedom\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/tyne/3761364.stm|title=Foster given Freedom of Gateshead|publisher=the BBC|date=20 October 2004|accessdate=29 August 2012}}</ref> Foster, who according to Gibson became \"the father of Gateshead athletics\",<ref name=\"Gibson 2004:1\">{{cite web|url=http://icnewcastle.icnetwork.co.uk/0200sport/0600athletics/tm_objectid=14208798%26method=full%26siteid=50081%26headline=face-to-face--brendan-foster-name_page.html|title=Face to Face: Brendan Foster|first=John|last=Gibson|work=[[Newcastle Evening Chronicle]]|date=4 May 2004|accessdate=28 December 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151230110849/http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/sport/other-sport/face-to-face-brendan-foster-1615997|archivedate=30 December 2015}} at p.1</ref> had been forced to train in [[Edinburgh]] during 1973 as a result of the poor condition of the Youth Stadium track.<ref name=\"UKA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.uka.org.uk/e-inspire/hall-of-fame-athletes/brendan-foster/|title=Brendan Foster|publisher=[[UK Athletics]]|year=2011|accessdate=29 August 2012}}</ref> In December 1973, he had been invited to a civic reception to celebrate his breaking of the two-mile world record earlier that year at Crystal Palace. At this reception, Foster was told that a new [[all-weather running track|synthetic track]] was being laid at Gateshead Youth Stadium. His response was a promise that, if the Council was serious, he would run at the stadium and break a world record (Foster later offered an explanation of that promise: \"You know how it is when you've had a few drinks&mdash;you promise the world!\").<ref name=\"ICN\"/> When the track was laid in early&nbsp;1974, Foster became convinced of the Council's sincerity.<ref name=\"ICN\"/> He was interviewed for the managerial position<ref name=\"ICN\"/> and, upon appointment, became the \"driving force\"<ref name=\"Freedom\"/> behind the programme of improvements to the Youth Stadium, which included the building of the main, covered Tyne and Wear stand in 1980<ref name=\"blue\"/> and three accompanying stands; the venue was renamed the Gateshead International Stadium.<ref name=\"gateshead1\"/><ref name=\"Freedom\"/> This first tranche of improvements cost around \u00a38&nbsp;million,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/history/domesday/dblock/GB-424000-561000/page/2|title=Domesday Reloaded: Gateshead International Stadium|publisher=[[BBC|the BBC]]|year=2011|accessdate=29 August 2012}}</ref> and Foster's proposal to commemorate the re-opening with an athletic event was approved, allowing for the first \"Gateshead Games\" to be held in 1974.<ref name=\"Gibson 2004:1\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1090986/2/index.htm|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151230112654/http://www.si.com/vault/1976/04/19/614810/howay-big-bren-yere-doin-us-prood|archivedate=30 December 2015|title=Howay, Big Bren! Ye're doin' us prood!|work=[[Sports Illustrated]]|first=Ray|last=Kennedy|date=19 April 1976|accessdate=8 March 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Tyne and wear stand.jpg|thumb|Young athletes run past the Tyne and Wear stand at Gateshead International Stadium]]The success of the first Gateshead Games, and their subsequent annual renewal, raised the profile of the stadium and caused Gateshead Council to further their financial investment. During the 1980s, additions were made to the site infrastructure, including the building of an indoor sports hall, outdoor football pitches and a gymnasium.<ref name=\"gateshead1\"/> In 1989 the running track was again relaid<ref name=\"TrackDir\"/> and Gateshead confirmed its reputation as a top-class athletics venue by hosting the [[European Cup (athletics)|Europa Cup]] (forerunner to the [[European Team Championships]]).<ref name=\"Europa1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/athletics/3007647/Athletics-Gateshead-glory-had-invigorating-effect.html|title=Gateshead glory had invigorating effect|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|last=Knight|first=Tom|date=20 June 2001|accessdate=31 August 2012}}</ref> In the 21st century, the site has been the subject of two major re-development projects. The first was completed in 2006, when two artificial outdoor football pitches, indoor athletic training facilities, sports science provisions and conferencing rooms were added at a cost of \u00a315&nbsp;million.<ref name=\"pitch up\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gateshead.gov.uk/Council%20and%20Democracy/news/News%20Articles/PITCH%20UP%20AT%20GATESHEAD%20INTERNATIONAL%20STADIUM.aspx|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060707180931/http://www.gateshead.gov.uk/Council%20and%20Democracy/news/News%20Articles/PITCH%20UP%20AT%20GATESHEAD%20INTERNATIONAL%20STADIUM.aspx|archivedate=7 July 2006|title=Pitch up at Gateshead International Stadium|publisher=Gateshead Council|date=27 June 2006|accessdate=31 August 2012}}</ref> The revamped stadium, funded by collaboration between [[One NorthEast]], [[Sport England]] and [[Gateshead College]] among others, was opened on 12 May 2006 by [[Sebastian Coe]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gateshead.gov.uk/Council%20and%20Democracy/news/News%20Articles/Lord%20Coe%20Opens%20New%20Development%20at%20Gateshead%20International%20Stadium.aspx |archive-url=https://archive.is/20121223155726/http://www.gateshead.gov.uk/Council%20and%20Democracy/news/News%20Articles/Lord%20Coe%20Opens%20New%20Development%20at%20Gateshead%20International%20Stadium.aspx |url-status=dead |archive-date=23 December 2012 |title=Lord Coe opens new development at Gateshead International Stadium |publisher=Gateshead Council |date=12 May 2006 |accessdate=31 August 2012 }}</ref>\n\nA second tranche of development, undertaken in two stages, was approved in November 2009.<ref name=\"Richards\">{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/north-east-news/evening-chronicle-news/2009/11/04/plans-to-revamp-gateshead-stadium-unveiled-72703-25089463/|title=Plans to revamp Gateshead Stadium unveiled |first=Linda|last=Richards|work=[[Evening Chronicle|Newcastle Evening Chronicle]]|date=4 November 2009|accessdate=31 August 2012}}</ref> This included a general refurbishment and improvement of the existing facilities at the stadium, adding cover, better toilet and new refreshment facilities to the exposed East Stand, improving wheelchair access, adding extra catering and conferencing facilities and a new media and management centre.<ref name=\"ALee\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gateshead.gov.uk/Leisure%20and%20Culture/sports1/news/development/GIS.aspx|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110213062619/http://www.gateshead.gov.uk/Leisure%20and%20Culture/sports1/news/development/GIS.aspx|archivedate=13 February 2011|title=Development Plans: Gateshead International Stadium|first=A|last=Lee|publisher=Gateshead Council|year=2010|accessdate=31 August 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"DB5\">Report to Cabinet &ndash; Gateshead International Stadium &ndash; Draft Development Brief, 2010: 5</ref> This was funded by collaboration between Gateshead Council, local development funds and Gateshead College.<ref name=\"ALee\"/> The covering of the 4,000-seat<ref name=\"Richards\"/> East Stand with a new canopy roof<ref>{{cite web|url=http://online.gateshead.gov.uk/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-27570/Item+06+-+Gateshead+International+Stadium+-+Tender+report.doc|archive-url=http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20111002092650/http://online.gateshead.gov.uk/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document%2D27570/Item%2B06%2B%2D%2BGateshead%2BInternational%2BStadium%2B%2D%2BTender%2Breport.doc|url-status=dead|archive-date=2 October 2011|title=Report to cabinet &ndash; Gateshead International Stadium (GIS) &ndash; Main Arena Tender|first=Dowling|last=Paul|publisher=Gateshead MBC|date=20 July 2010|accessdate= 28 December 2012}} at p.1</ref> was completed in July 2010, immediately prior to Gateshead hosting a [[2010 IAAF Diamond League|Diamond League]] event.<ref name=\"covered\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gateshead.gov.uk/Council%20and%20Democracy/news/News%20Articles/GatesheadInternationalStadiumimprovements.aspx|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110918124501/http://www.gateshead.gov.uk/Council%20and%20Democracy/news/News%20Articles/GatesheadInternationalStadiumimprovements.aspx|archivedate=18 September 2011|title=Gateshead International Stadium Improvements; Spectators to be covered in glory in time for sprinting champions head to head |publisher=Gateshead Council|date=12 July 2010|accessdate=31 August 2012}}</ref> The second stage of the re-development\u2014the building of the corporate and media facilities\u2014commenced on 6&nbsp;September 2010 and was completed on time in summer&nbsp;2011.<ref name=\"ALee\"/> The total cost of the work was estimated to be \u00a37.6&nbsp;million.<ref name=\"DB5\"/>\n\nA third programme of expansion was initially mooted in 2008. The aim of this programme was to expand the stadium into an all-embracing \"sports village\",<ref>Report to Cabinet &ndash; Gateshead International Stadium &ndash; Draft Development Brief, 2010: 3</ref> replete with an ice rink, indoor golf course, restaurants and shops. Gateshead Council invited tenders in August 2008 from commercial organisations interested in undertaking the development.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/tyne/7579943.stm|title=Ice arena plan at sports stadium|publisher=BBC|date=24 August 2008|accessdate=31 August 2012}}</ref> A formal draft development brief was compiled and published in November 2009.<ref>Report to Cabinet &ndash; Gateshead International Stadium &ndash; Draft Development Brief, 2010</ref> A report to Council in December 2009 noted that there had been \"a reasonable level of interest at the preliminary stage\" from private investors, but that only one detailed proposal had been submitted, which had been declined by the Council on financial grounds.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://online.gateshead.gov.uk/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-26069/Item+15+-+Gateshead+International+Stadium+(GIS)+%E2%80%93+Revised+Draft+Development+Brief+report.doc|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111002120617/http://online.gateshead.gov.uk/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-26069/Item+15+-+Gateshead+International+Stadium+%28GIS%29+%E2%80%93+Revised+Draft+Development+Brief+report.doc|url-status=dead|archive-date=2 October 2011|title=Gateshead International Stadium (GIS) &ndash; Revised Draft Development Brief|first=Derek|last=Quinn|publisher=Gateshead MBC|date=15 December 2009|accessdate=28 December 2012}} at p.1</ref> The report also noted concerns that the original centrepiece of the proposed village, the ice rink, may have been deterring investors and that a similar proposal to redevelop land at the [[Stadium of Light]] in [[Sunderland, Tyne and Wear|Sunderland]] was detracting from what councillors had hoped to be a unique feature of the proposed village.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://online.gateshead.gov.uk/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-26069/Item+15+-+Gateshead+International+Stadium+(GIS)+%E2%80%93+Revised+Draft+Development+Brief+report.doc|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111002120617/http://online.gateshead.gov.uk/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-26069/Item+15+-+Gateshead+International+Stadium+%28GIS%29+%E2%80%93+Revised+Draft+Development+Brief+report.doc|url-status=dead|archive-date=2 October 2011|title=Gateshead International Stadium (GIS) &ndash; Revised Draft Development Brief|first=Derek|last=Quinn|publisher=Gateshead MBC|date=15 December 2009|accessdate=28 December 2012}} at p.7</ref> The result was that a fresh proposal was raised to remove the ice rink from the brief in an attempt to \"stimulate the market\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://online.gateshead.gov.uk/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-26069/Item+15+-+Gateshead+International+Stadium+(GIS)+%E2%80%93+Revised+Draft+Development+Brief+report.doc|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111002120617/http://online.gateshead.gov.uk/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-26069/Item+15+-+Gateshead+International+Stadium+%28GIS%29+%E2%80%93+Revised+Draft+Development+Brief+report.doc|url-status=dead|archive-date=2 October 2011|title=Gateshead International Stadium (GIS) &ndash; Revised Draft Development Brief|first=Derek|last=Quinn|publisher=Gateshead MBC|date=15 December 2009|accessdate=28 December 2012}} at p.8</ref> A public consultation was undertaken and in May 2010 the council reported that 327 of the 375 responses received were in favour of the amended proposal.<ref name=\"Dowling\">{{cite web|url=http://online.gateshead.gov.uk/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-27194/Item+10+-1-+Gateshead+International+Stadium+(GIS)+%E2%80%93+Development+Brief+report.doc|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111002102429/http://online.gateshead.gov.uk/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-27194/Item+10+-1-+Gateshead+International+Stadium+%28GIS%29+%E2%80%93+Development+Brief+report.doc|url-status=dead|archive-date=2 October 2011|title=Report to cabinet &ndash; Gateshead International Stadium (GIS) &ndash; Development Brief|first=Dowling|last=Paul|publisher=Gateshead MBC|date=25 May 2010|accessdate=28 December 2012}} at p.1</ref> As a result, notice was given to developers that the council intended to market the site and ten responses were received.<ref name=\"Dowling\"/>\n\n==Structure and facilities==\n\n[[File:Gateshead International Stadium Layout.png|thumb|Diagram demonstrating layout of main arena at Gateshead International Stadium<ref name=\"UKA Aviva\"/>]]Gateshead International Stadium and its facilities occupy {{convert|24.4|ha|acre}} of land.<ref>Report to Cabinet &ndash; Gateshead International Stadium &ndash; Draft Development Brief, 2010: 7 at para.17</ref> The main athletics arena at Gateshead International Stadium is an [[All-seater stadium|all-seater]], bowl-shaped arena consisting of four stands of seats.<ref name=\"blue\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bluesqfootball.com/story/0,20970,13036_3770978,00.html |title=Gateshead |publisher=Bluesquarefootball.com |year=2012 |accessdate=26 September 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121018180435/http://www.bluesqfootball.com/story/0%2C20970%2C13036_3770978%2C00.html |archivedate=18 October 2012 }}</ref> The precise capacity of the venue is uncertain; some sources claim it to be 11,750,<ref name=\"Quinn\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gateshead-fc.com/gateshead-international-stadium |title=Gateshead International Stadium |publisher=[[Gateshead F.C.]] |year=2012 |accessdate=26 September 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120801005617/http://www.gateshead-fc.com/gateshead-international-stadium |archivedate=1 August 2012 }}</ref> others 11,762<ref name=\"TrackDir\"/> and some provide a figure of 11,800.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thunderrugby.com/page.php?id=970|title=Gateshead International Stadium&nbsp;- Home of Thunder|publisher=[[Newcastle Thunder|Gateshead Thunder]]|year=2012|accessdate=26 September 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120707171821/http://www.thunderrugby.com/page.php?id=970|archivedate=7 July 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gateshead-fc.com/4125/media-watch-grounds-for-hope-over-new-gateshead-fc-stadium |title=Media Watch &ndash; Grounds for hope over new Gateshead FC stadium |first=Steve |last=Brown |publisher=[[Gateshead F.C.]] |date=23 August 2012 |accessdate=26 September 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120926044906/http://www.gateshead-fc.com/4125/media-watch-grounds-for-hope-over-new-gateshead-fc-stadium |archivedate=26 September 2012 }}</ref> The main stand is the Tyne and Wear Stand, a steep, [[cantilever]]ed structure<ref name=\"blue\"/> seating 3,300 spectators.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gateshead-fc.com/2487/fa-cup-gateshead-v-brentford-saturday-7th-november-match-information |title=FA Cup: Gateshead v Brentford &nbsp;- Saturday 7th November &nbsp;- Match Information |publisher=[[Gateshead F.C.]] |date=4 November 2009 |accessdate=26 September 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151126120232/http://www.gateshead-fc.com/2487/fa-cup-gateshead-v-brentford-saturday-7th-november-match-information |archivedate=26 November 2015 }}</ref> This stand contains toilet and catering facilities and a bar area.<ref name=\"blue\"/> Opposite is the East Stand, a 4,000-seat structure that was uncovered until 2010, when a cantilevered [[Canopy (building)|canopy]] roof was added. A bespoke design by Fabric Architecture, the roof is a {{convert|30|m|ft}} structure incorporating five [[barrel vault]] forms.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cms.esi.info/Media/documents/80083_1308047032870.pdf|title=Fabric architecture Ltd&nbsp;- Case study: Gateshead International Stadium|publisher=Fabric Architecture|year=2009|accessdate=26 September 2012}}</ref> Part of the same improvement plan added toilet and catering facilities to the East Stand.<ref name=\"covered\"/> The South Terrace, sometimes referred to as simply the South Stand,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/north-east-news/evening-chronicle-news/2012/07/17/queen-to-visit-gateshead-and-newcastle-tomorrow-72703-31410354/ |title=Replay our blog from the Queen's visit to Tyneside |work=[[Evening Chronicle|Newcastle Evening Chronicle]] |date=18 July 2012 |accessdate=9 November 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120822011058/http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/north-east-news/evening-chronicle-news/2012/07/17/queen-to-visit-gateshead-and-newcastle-tomorrow-72703-31410354/ |archivedate=22 August 2012 }}</ref> consists of a continuous, uncovered bank of seating in eight blocks with access through four [[turnstiles]].<ref name=\"UKA Aviva\">{{cite web|url=http://www.uka.org.uk/training-zone/2010/aviva-british-grand-prix/|title=Aviva British Grand Prix|publisher=[[UK Athletics]]|date=10 July 2010|accessdate=9 November 2012}}</ref> The North Terrace is opposite and consists of two blocks of uncovered seating separated by a large scoreboard.<ref name=\"UKA Aviva\"/>\n\n[[File:For athletics.jpg|thumb|left|Hurdles set out on the sprint straight in 2010]]The athletics track in the main arena was laid in 2003 and is an [[International Association of Athletics Federations]] (IAAF) standard 400m eight-lane oval. It is a polymer synthetic [[tartan track]] with a depth of {{convert|3|cm|in|2}}. The sprint straight consists of eight lanes and is situated in front of the Tyne and Wear Stand, adjacent to the [[long jump|long]] and [[triple jump]] area. A height-adjustable water jump, for use in [[Steeplechase (athletics)|steeplechase racing]], is located on the inside of the track.<ref name=\"TrackDir\"/><ref name=\"UKA Aviva\"/><ref name=\"MBCfacts\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gateshead.gov.uk/Leisure%20and%20Culture/sports1/facilities/GIS/home.aspx|title=Gateshead International Stadium|publisher=Gateshead Council|year=2012|accessdate=9 November 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120908102711/https://www.gateshead.gov.uk/Leisure%20and%20Culture/sports1/facilities/GIS/home.aspx|archive-date=8 September 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Floodlights (sport)|Floodlights]] allow athletics events to be held at night.<ref name=\"TrackDir\"/> The inner track area, which is floodlit, is an IAAF standard-sized grass surface used for athletics field events, rugby and football.<ref name=\"MBCfacts\"/> When used for the latter, the pitch dimensions are {{convert|100|x|64|m|yd|1}}.<ref name=\"blue\"/>\n\nThe main arena is supplemented by other facilities. To the rear of the North Terrace are two [[Artificial turf|third generation artificial]] pitches that are [[UEFA]] licensed, fully floodlit and full-sized for use in competitive rugby, football and American football.<ref name=\"pitch up\"/> Alongside them are two grassed and one sand-dressed playing areas, which are also floodlit.<ref name=\"pitch up\"/><ref name=\"MBCfacts\"/> Behind the Tyne and Wear Stand is an indoor sports hall, which contains a {{convert|33|x|44|m|yd|1}} playing area marked out for various sports including badminton, netball and tennis.<ref name=\"MBCfacts\"/> A retractable indoor athletics facility was previously housed alongside the sports hall, consisting of a {{convert|50|m|yd}} long synthetic sprint straight and areas for throwing and jumping events, but its mechanical operation proved problematic<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.runtrackdir.com/details.asp?track=gateshead-s-indoor|title=Gateshead International Stadium Indoor Track|publisher=Running Track Directory|first=Tim|last=Grose|date=30 May 1999|accessdate=9 November 2012}}</ref> and a more modern structure replaced it in 2006. This facility has a {{convert|60|m|yd}} sprint straight in an {{convert|82|m|yd}} hall, throwing and jumping facilities, a weights room and gymnasium.<ref name=\"MBCfacts\"/>\n\n==Athletics==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"float: right; margin-left: 2em; width: 40%; font-size: 90%;\" cellspacing=\"3\"\n|-\n!colspan=\"4\"|World record performances at Gateshead Stadium\n|-\n|'''Athlete name'''||'''Event'''||'''Record mark'''||'''Date'''\n|-\n|{{flagathlete|[[Brendan Foster]]|GBR}}||[[3000 metres|3000m]]||7:35.20||3 August 1974<ref name=\"Gibson 2004:1\"/><ref name=\"UKA\"/>\n|-\n|{{flagathlete|[[Daniela Bartova]]|CZE}}||[[Pole vault]]||4.14m||2 July 1995<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/07/06/sports/track-and-field-american-sprinters-race-past-top-fields.html?pagewanted=2|title=Track and Field; American Sprinters Race Past Top Fields|work=[[The New York Times]]|first=Christopher|last=Clarey|date=6 July 1995|accessdate=22 December 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{flagathlete|[[Yelena Isinbayeva]]|RUS}}||[[Pole vault]]||4.82m||13 July 2003<ref name=\"autogenerated2003\">{{cite web|url=http://www.iaaf.org/news/printer,newsid=21992.htmx|title=Women's World Pole Vault record for Isinbayeva in Gateshead|publisher=[[IAAF]]|date=14 July 2003|accessdate=9 September 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{flagathlete|[[Yelena Isinbayeva]]|RUS}}||[[Pole vault]]||4.87m||27 June 2004<ref name=\"IAAF\">{{cite web|url=http://www.iaaf.org/history/GP/season=2004/news/Kind=2/newsId=25753.html|title=Isinbayeva raises World record to 4.87 in Gateshead|publisher=[[IAAF]]|date=27 June 2004|accessdate=9 September 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{flagathlete|[[Asafa Powell]]|JAM}}||[[100 metres|100m]]||9.77||11 June 2006<ref name=\"rowbottom2006\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/general/athletics-powell-thrills-british-crowd-by-equalling-world-100m-record-482065.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160106153307/http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/general/athletics-powell-thrills-british-crowd-by-equalling-world-100m-record-6098477.html|archivedate=6 January 2016|title=Athletics: Powell thrills British crowd by equalling world 100m record|first=Mike|last=Rowbottom|work=[[The Independent]]|date=12 June 2006|accessdate=9 September 2012}}</ref>\n|}\n\nThe first major athletic event held at the stadium was the Vaux Breweries International Athletics meet in July 1961. According to its sponsors, the highlight of this meet was the team three-mile race, won by the Blackpool and Fylde Athletic club who were awarded a gold tankard as their prize.<ref name=\"BGR\"/> Attracted by a prize fund of \u00a3500 and the imminent [[AAA Championships]] in London, the event attracted several athletes from New Zealand, including [[Athletics at the 1960 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 5000 metres|reigning 5000m metre Olympic champion]] [[Murray Halberg]] and [[Peter Snell]], the [[Athletics at the 1960 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 800 metres|reigning 800m Olympic champion]].<ref name=\"McGuirk\"/> Watched by a capacity crowd of 10,000 spectators, the men won their respective races; Halberg placed first in the [[Mile run|mile]] with a time of 4:03:70 and Snell led a [[New Zealand]] one-two in the 880-yard event, finishing ahead of teammate Gary Philpott in 1:50:40.<ref name=\"McGuirk\"/>\n\nWhen the comprehensive refurbishment of the stadium was completed more than a decade later, Brendan Foster (by this time a Gateshead Council employee) proposed an international athletics meet. On 3&nbsp;August 1974, the first \"Gateshead Games\" were staged in front of around 10,000 spectators.<ref name=\"Gibson 2004:1\"/><ref name=\"UKA\"/> Four weeks before he won the European 5000m title at the [[1974 European Athletics Championships]] in Rome, Foster kept his earlier promise to run in the men's 3000m and won the race in a new world-record time of 7:35:20. According to journalist John Gibson, Foster's performance gave the meet, broadcast live by [[Tyne Tees Television]], \"landmark status\".<ref name=\"Gibson 2004:1\"/><ref name=\"UKA\"/> A plaque commemorating the record was later placed at the entrance to the stadium.<ref name=\"ICN\"/>\n\nThe Gateshead Games became an annual event, which gave the stadium credibility as a major sporting venue.<ref name=\"ICN\"/><ref name=\"Gibson 2004:1\"/> In his managerial capacity with Gateshead Council, Foster was increasingly able to attract athletes to the games. In 1977, Foster had to intervene when [[BBC Radio Newcastle]] provided the wrong [[Ethiopian national anthem]] which, when played, offended [[Miruts Yifter]] sufficiently that he and his teammates started off towards [[Newcastle International Airport]]. The intervention worked\u2014in the end, Foster asked Yifter and his teammates if they would sing the anthem themselves, which they did in the middle of the stadium\u2014and Yifter returned to outclass a field including [[Steve Ovett]] over 5000m.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://icnewcastle.icnetwork.co.uk/0200sport/0600athletics/tm_objectid=14208798%26method=full%26siteid=50081%26headline=face-to-face--brendan-foster-name_page.html |title=Face to Face: Brendan Foster |first=John |last=Gibson |work=[[Newcastle Evening Chronicle]] |date=4 May 2004 |accessdate=28 December 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151230110849/http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/sport/other-sport/face-to-face-brendan-foster-1615997 |archivedate=30 December 2015 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref> The track was resurfaced by Regisport in 1982<ref name=\"TrackDir\">{{cite web|url=http://www.runtrackdir.com/details.asp?track=gateshead&country=uk|title=Gateshead International Stadium|publisher=Running Track Directory|date=25 March 2010|accessdate=30 August 2012}} This site is a redirect from the UK Athletics website.</ref> and the venues' profile was further raised in the summer of 1983, when Gateshead-born athlete [[Steve Cram]]{{refn|group=nb|UK Athletics state that Cram was born in Gateshead,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uka.org.uk/e-inspire/hall-of-fame-athletes/steve-cram/|title=Hall of Fame Athletes &ndash; Steve Cram|publisher=[[UK Athletics]]|year=2012|accessdate=11 November 2012}}</ref> as does an interview with Cram by ''Track and Field News'' in September 1985.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.trackandfieldnews.com/archive/Interviews/Steve%20Cram.pdf |title=T & F N &ndash; Interview, Steve Cram |work=Track and Field News |first=Steve |last=Powell |date=12 September 1985 |accessdate=12 November 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130524060213/http://www.trackandfieldnews.com/archive/Interviews/Steve%20Cram.pdf |archivedate=24 May 2013 }}</ref> Other sources, including an article from the [[University of Sunderland]] website, claim he was born in [[Jarrow]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://services.sunderland.ac.uk/universitysport/newsevents/news/news/index.php?nid=500|title=News Story &ndash; Steve Cram named new Chancellor|publisher=[[University of Sunderland]]|date=23 May 2008|accessdate=12 November 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120321190504/http://services.sunderland.ac.uk/universitysport/newsevents/news/news/index.php?nid=500|archivedate=21 March 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>}} faced Sebastian Coe over 800m in the Gateshead Games. In front of a reported crowd of 15,000 who were \"shoehorned into the bowl\" and millions more watching on BBC's [[Sunday Grandstand]], Cram prevailed to spark \"pandemonium\" in his final race before winning the gold medal at the [[1983 World Championships in Athletics|1983 World Athletics Championships]] in Helsinki.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/sport/other-sport/face-to-face-steve-cram-1533194 |title=Face to Face: Steve Cram |first=John |last=Gibson |work=[[Newcastle Evening Chronicle]] |date=2 May 2006 |accessdate=2 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 1989, Gateshead hosted the [[1989 European Cup (athletics)|Europa Cup]]. The men's competition was won for the first time by a Great Britain team captained by [[Linford Christie]] and which included [[Kriss Akabusi]] and [[Jack Buckner]]; the event was described a decade later as having had an \"invigorating effect\" on those who were in attendance.<ref name=\"Europa1\"/> Four years later, on 30 July 1993, a stadium-record crowd of 14,797<ref name=\"McGuirk\"/> watched Christie, by this time [[Athletics at the 1992 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 100 metres|the reigning 100m Olympic champion]], in action again &ndash; this time against his old rival [[Carl Lewis]] in a race where both men were reportedly paid \u00a3100,000 irrespective of the result.<ref name=\"Rowbottom\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/athletics-climate-and-form-point-to-a-christie-victory-world-and-olympic-champions-play-down-the-implications-of-tonights-gateshead-showdown-for-world-championships-in-stuttgart-1488119.html|title=Athletics: Climate and form point to a Christie victory: World and Olympic champions play down the implications of tonight's Gateshead showdown for World Championships in Stuttgart|first=Mike|last=Rowbottom|work=[[The Independent]]|date=30 July 1993|accessdate=9 September 2012}}</ref> Christie won in a time of 10.07 seconds, ahead of [[Jon Drummond]] in second and Lewis, who finished \"a distant third\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/general/athletics/jamaican-sprinters-yohan-blake-and-usain-bolt-refuse-to-race-headtohead-8092692.html|title=Jamaican sprinters Yohan Blake and Usain Bolt refuse to race head-to-head |first=Simon|last=Turnbull|work=[[The Independent]]|date=30 August 2012|accessdate=9 September 2012}}</ref> The 100m race was the highlight of the \"high profile\" Vauxhall Invitational meet, which was televised in the UK by [[ITV (TV channel)|ITV]] and watched by around 10 million viewers. [[Michael Johnson (sprinter)|Michael Johnson]], [[John Regis (athlete)|John Regis]] and Steve Cram competed in various events at the Vauxhall Invitational.<ref name=\"Rowbottom\"/>\n\nIn August 1998, Gateshead was selected to host the [[2000 European Cup (athletics)|2000 Europa Cup]] after the [[European Athletic Association]] switched the event from original host venue [[Martinique]] to avoid athletes travelling long distances in an Olympic year.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/athletics-gatesheads-european-cup-1173824.html|title=Athletics: Gateshead's European Cup|work=[[The Independent]]|date=24 August 1998|accessdate=9 September 2012}}</ref> This made Gateshead the first venue to host the event twice.<ref name=\"Diamond\">{{cite web|url=http://www.diamondleague.com/News/News-Archive/An-athletics-snapshot-of-GATESHEAD/|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130121222720/http://www.diamondleague.com/News/News-Archive/An-athletics-snapshot-of-GATESHEAD/|url-status=dead|archive-date=21 January 2013|title=An athletic snapshot of Gateshead|first=David|last=Powell|publisher=Diamond League.com|date=20 November 2009|accessdate=9 September 2012}}</ref> On 16&ndash;17 July 2000, spectators at Gateshead once again saw Great Britain's men's team take the title, this time by half a point from Germany in second place; the British victory came despite missing ten first-choice team members. The women's event was won by Russia, who defeated second-placed Germany by thirteen points.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/athletics/4759741/European-Cup-Athletics-Relay-squad-find-Britains-winning-kick.html|title=European Cup Athletics: Relay squad find Britain's winning kick|first=Brendan|last=Gallagher|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=17 July 2000|accessdate=9 September 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Paula Radcliffe 2005.jpg|right|upright|border|thumb|[[Paula Radcliffe]] runs the 10,000m at Gateshead in 2004]]Foster's \"Gateshead Games\" had become the [[British Grand Prix (athletics)|British Grand Prix]] by 2003, and on 13 July 21-year-old [[Yelena Isinbayeva]] set a [[Women's pole vault world record progression|new world record]] of 4.82m in the women's [[pole vault]] event. Isinbayeva's achievement in the last event of the meet was so unexpected that only 1,000 of the 10,000 spectators witnessed it, the rest having left early. For her achievement, she was given a bonus cheque for $50,000.<ref name=\"autogenerated2003\"/> On 27 June 2004, Isinbayeva returned to Gateshead. This time the event organisers decided to schedule the pole vault event earlier and were rewarded when Isinbayeva defied extremely windy conditions to post a new record mark of 4.87m.<ref name=\"IAAF\"/> Isinbayeva was the second woman to set a world record in the pole vault at Gateshead; [[Daniela Bartova]] did so in 1995.<ref name=\"Diamond\"/> In 2006, a crowd of 8,500 saw [[Asafa Powell]] equal the world record of 9.77 seconds in the [[100 metres|men's 100m]]. The official, un-rounded time of 9.762 seconds was then the fastest time ever recorded. The meet was also notable for the return to competition of [[Dwain Chambers]] after his ban for using [[Tetrahydrogestrinone|performance-enhancing drugs]], and for [[Eliud Kipchoge]] breaking Foster's stadium record over 3000m that had stood for more than three decades.<ref name=\"rowbottom2006\"/>\n\nIn 2010, the British Grand Prix at Gateshead was chosen as one of the inaugural fourteen [[IAAF Diamond League 2010|Diamond League]] events,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uka.org.uk/media/news/news-archive-pre-2011/april-2010/30-04-10-gay/|title=Diamond League|publisher=[[UK Athletics]]|date=30 April 2010|accessdate=9 September 2012}}</ref> but although competitors included [[Tyson Gay]], Powell, [[Jessica Ennis]] and [[Vincent Chepkok]], the attendance was unusually poor, causing the local press to wonder whether Gateshead's contract for the marquee event would be renewed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.journallive.co.uk/newcastle-sports/newcastle-sports/athletics-news/2010/07/12/tyson-gay-beats-asafa-powell-at-gateshead-stadium-61634-26831826/|title=Tyson Gay beats Asafa Powell at Gateshead Stadium|first=Stuart|last=Rayner|work=[[The Journal (newspaper)|The Journal]]|date=12 July 2010|accessdate=9 September 2012}}</ref> Those fears were to prove well-founded when [[UK Athletics]] agreed to a three-year contract to stage the event at the [[Alexander Stadium]] in Birmingham.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uka.org.uk/media/news/news-archive-pre-2011/november-2010/22-11-10-aviva-birmingham-grand-prix/|title=aviva birmingham grand prix|publisher=[[UK Athletics]]|date=22 November 2010|accessdate=9 September 2012}}</ref> The move prompted one reporter to lament that \"the switch is a major blow to both Gateshead International Stadium and North-East sport in general, but can hardly be regarded as a major surprise given the dwindling support for major athletics events in the region.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/sport/8679464.North_East_athletics_loses_its_flagship_event/|title=North-East athletics loses its flagship event|first=Scott|last=Wilson|work=[[The Northern Echo]]|date=21 November 2010|accessdate=9 September 2012}}</ref>\n\nThis loss was mitigated somewhat by the European Athletic Association's decision to award Gateshead the [[2013 European Team Championships]], the successor to the Europa Cup.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.european-athletics.org/competitions/european-team-championships/news/article=gateshead-host-2013-European-athletics-team-championships/index.html |title=Gateshead to host 2013 European Athletics Team Championships |publisher=[[European Athletics Association]] |date=June 2011 |accessdate=2 October 2016}}</ref> In doing so, Gateshead became the only stadium to host the European Team Championships on three occasions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.athleticsweekly.com/news/gateshead-awarded-2013-european-team-championships/ |title=Gateshead awarded 2013 European Team Championships |work=[[Athletics Weekly]] |date=6 June 2011 |accessdate=9 September 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110816005537/http://www.athleticsweekly.com/news/gateshead-awarded-2013-european-team-championships/ |archivedate=16 August 2011 }}</ref> The championships were held on 22&ndash;23 June 2013 amid very wet and windy conditions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/athletics/23023977|title=European team Championships: GB secure third place|publisher=[[BBC|the BBC]]|date=23 June 2015|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref> On the first day of competition, [[Mo Farah]] ran a 50.89 second final lap in winning the men's 5000m to help the home team into third place on 181 points, behind Russia (194 points) and Germany (195 points).<ref>{{cite book|title=Souped-up Mo Farah turns into Billy Whizz at the European Team Championships|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/general/athletics/souped-up-mo-farah-turns-into-billy-whizz-at-the-european-team-championships-8669844.html|work=[[The Independent]]|first=Simon|last=Turnbull|date=22 June 2013|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref> Despite a strong start, the Great Britain team were unable to make up the deficit on the second day of competition and finished in third place overall on 338 points, behind runners-up Germany (347.5 points) and the champions Russia (354.5 points).<ref>{{cite book|title=GB youngsters delight Peter Eriksson at European Team Championships |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2013/jun/23/gb-peter-eriksson-european-team-championships|work=[[The Guardian]]|first=Sean|last=Ingle|date=23 June 2013|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nDue to redevelopment of Birmingham\u2019s Alexander Stadium for the [[2022 Commonwealth Games|2022 commonwealth games]], the [[British Grand Prix (athletics)|British Grand Prix]] Diamond League fixture is set to return to Gateshead in 2020 for the first time in 10 years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.athleticsweekly.com/athletics-news/gateshead-included-in-2020-diamond-league-season-1039926187/|title=Gateshead included in 2020 Diamond League season|last=|first=|date=October 22, 2019|website=Athletics Weekly|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 30, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Tenants==\n\n===Gateshead Football Club===\n{{main|Gateshead F.C.}}\nThe stadium was briefly used by former Football League members [[Gateshead A.F.C.]] after leaving [[Redheugh Park]] in 1971, but the club went bust in 1973.<ref name=UD>Paul Smith & Shirley Smith (2005) ''The Ultimate Directory of English & Scottish Football League Grounds Second Edition 1888\u20132005'', Yore Publications, p70, {{ISBN|0954783042}}</ref> The following year South Shields football club relocated to Gateshead and were renamed [[Gateshead United F.C.|Gateshead United]]; they played at the Gateshead Stadium from 1974 to 1977 when they folded and [[Gateshead F.C.]] was formed.<ref name=\"GFC history\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gateshead-fc.com/club-history|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130206113453/http://www.gateshead-fc.com/club-history|url-status=dead|archive-date=6 February 2013|title=The History of Gateshead Football Club|first=Jeff|last=Bowron|publisher=[[Gateshead F.C.]]|year=2012|accessdate=15 September 2012}}</ref>\n\nGateshead F.C. have been tenants since their formation in 1977.<ref name=\"GFC history\"/> In May 2008 Gateshead hosted [[Buxton F.C.|Buxton]] in a promotion play-off and won 2&ndash;0 in front of 1,402 spectators, the largest crowd to watch the club at the ground in 14 years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Bogie%27s+over+the+Toon+with+victory%3B+Gateshead+clinch+promotion+with...-a0178633259|title=Bogie's over the Toon with victory|first=Jeff|last=Bowron|work=[[Evening Chronicle|Newcastle Evening Chronicle]]|date=5 May 2008|accessdate=22 December 2012}}</ref> That record was broken a year later when 4,121 saw Gateshead defeat [[A.F.C. Telford United|Telford United]] 2&ndash;0 on 9&nbsp;May 2009 to win promotion to the [[Conference Premier]] league.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gateshead-fc.com/2282/gateshead-1-0-afc-telford-united |title=Gateshead 1&ndash;0 AFC Telford United |first=Jeff |last=Bowron |publisher=[[Gateshead F.C.]] |date=10 May 2009 |accessdate=15 September 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120830031215/http://www.gateshead-fc.com/2282/gateshead-1-0-afc-telford-united |archivedate=30 August 2012 }}</ref> The current record attendance for a competitive fixture stands at 8,144, set on 4&nbsp;May 2014 when Gateshead played host to [[Grimsby Town F.C.|Grimsby Town]] in the second leg of the [[2013-14 Football Conference#Play-offs|Conference Premier play-off]] semi-final.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/27193080|title=Gateshead 3&ndash;1 Grimsby Town|first=Joe|last=Townsend|publisher=[[BBC|the BBC]]|date=4 May 2014|accessdate=21 May 2014}}</ref> Gateshead won 3-1 to progress to the final at [[Wembley Stadium]] where they were beaten 2-1 by [[Cambridge United F.C.|Cambridge United]]. The defeat consigned the club to a 55th consecutive season outside the Football League.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/27360422|title=Cambridge 2&ndash;1 Gateshead|first=Chris|last=Osborne|publisher=[[BBC|the BBC]]|date=18 May 2014|accessdate=21 May 2014}}</ref> Gateshead F.C. continue to play at Gateshead Stadium but, according to North East Life magazine, it is \"a fine but inappropriate stadium&nbsp;... as a football ground it can be a soulless home\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://northeast.greatbritishlife.co.uk/article/gateshead-fc-dare-to-dream-37130/ |title=Gateshead FC dare to dream |publisher=North East Life |year=2012 |accessdate=15 September 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140515155612/http://www.northeastlifemag.co.uk/out-about/gateshead_fc_dare_to_dream_1_1648041 |archivedate=15 May 2014 |url-status=dead}}</ref> In 2009, chairman Graham Wood unveiled plans to move to a new, purpose-built 9,000 capacity ground on Prince Consort Road in the centre of Gateshead.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/tyne/8330448.stm|title=Football stadium plans unveiled|publisher=[[BBC|the BBC]]|date=28 October 2009|accessdate=15 September 2012}}</ref> Detailed proposals were published soon after,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gateshead-fc.com/new-stadium |title=Gateshead's New Stadium |publisher=[[Gateshead F.C.]] |year=2009 |accessdate=15 September 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120831210336/http://www.gateshead-fc.com/new-stadium |archivedate=31 August 2012 }}</ref> and Wood told local media in 2012 that he expects the move to increase crowds and alleviate the financial constraints on him as he continues to bankroll the club; it is estimated that crowds would need to reach 3,000 regularly for the club to operate profitably from Gateshead Stadium.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/sport/football/non-league-football/2012/08/23/grounds-for-hope-over-new-gateshead-fc-stadium-72703-31679339/|title=Grounds for hope over new Gateshead FC stadium|work=[[Evening Chronicle|Newcastle Evening Chronicle]]|first=Steve|last=Brown|date=23 August 2012|accessdate=28 December 2012}}</ref> According to the original proposal, the stadium was expected to be ready for the 2012&ndash;13 season, but financing has been difficult and the proposed move is now on hold.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/sport/football/non-league-football/2011/06/06/optimism-over-gateshead-s-new-stadium-plans-72703-28827957/ |title=Optimism over Gateshead's new stadium plans |work=[[Evening Chronicle|Newcastle Evening Chronicle]] |date=6 June 2011 |accessdate=28 December 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110625011823/http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/sport/football/non-league-football/2011/06/06/optimism-over-gateshead-s-new-stadium-plans-72703-28827957/ |archivedate=25 June 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.journallive.co.uk/north-east-news/todays-news/2012/10/09/athletes-forced-to-make-way-for-footballers-at-gateshead-stadium-61634-31994732/|title=Athletes forced to make way for footballers at Gateshead Stadium|work=[[The Journal (newspaper)|The Journal]]|first=Michael|last=Brown|date=9 October 2012|accessdate=28 December 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Gateshead Harriers===\n\n[[Gateshead Harriers]] are an athletic club based at Gateshead International Stadium. Founded in 1904 as Gateshead St Mary's Church Running Club, they were initially a men-only club until allowing the admission of women in 1951. The club moved to the Gateshead Youth Stadium in 1956, making the Harriers the stadium's oldest tenant.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gateshead-harriers.co.uk/home/ |title=Welcome to Gateshead Harriers |publisher=Gateshead Harriers |year=2012 |accessdate=16 September 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120628164804/http://www.gateshead-harriers.co.uk/home/ |archivedate=28 June 2012 }}</ref> In 2006 they won promotion to the first division of the [[British Athletics League]] and were the only club from the north-east of England to compete at that level.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/sport/other-sport/harriers-join-big-league-1533578|title=Harriers join big league|first=Bill|last=McGuirk|work=[[Evening Chronicle|Newcastle Evening Chronicle]]|date=4 May 2006|accessdate=2 October 2016}}</ref> After a six-year stay in the division, the Harriers were relegated to division two in August 2012 after failing to win enough points at the final meet of the season at Eton to prevent a bottom-two league finish.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/sport/athletics-news/2012/08/20/battling-gateshead-harriers-fail-to-beat-relegation-72703-31656928/|title=Battling Gateshead Harriers fail to beat relegation|work=[[Evening Chronicle|Newcastle Evening Chronicle]]|date=22 August 2012|accessdate=16 September 2012}}</ref> Club officials received over 100 new applications for membership in the aftermath of [[2012 Olympics|the 2012 London Olympics]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/sport/athletics-news/2012/08/30/london-2012-olympics-legacy-is-up-and-running-72703-31725773/|title=London 2012 Olympics legacy is up and running|first=Bill|last=McGuirk|work=[[Evening Chronicle|Newcastle Evening Chronicle]]|date=30 August 2012|accessdate=16 September 2012}}</ref>\n\nAt least one Gateshead Harrier has taken part in every Olympics and [[Paralympic Games|Paralympics]] held since 1972.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gateshead.gov.uk/People%20and%20Living/award/award.aspx|title=The Gateshead Award|publisher=Gateshead Council|year=2012|accessdate=16 September 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120916144454/http://www.gateshead.gov.uk/People%20and%20Living/award/award.aspx|archive-date=16 September 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Notable alumni include Brendan Foster, who joined the club aged 17 and later claimed that \"my first aim was to be the best runner of Gateshead Harriers\".<ref>Luhtala, 2002: 94</ref> Foster, inducted into the [[England Athletics Hall of Fame]] in 2010 and recently voted the eleventh \"greatest [[Geordie]]\" in a local poll, later became the president of Gateshead Harriers and remains so as of 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/sport/athletics-news/2010/11/04/brendan-foster-inducted-into-hall-of-fame-72703-27599438/ |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120729152531/http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/sport/athletics-news/2010/11/04/brendan-foster-inducted-into-hall-of-fame-72703-27599438/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=29 July 2012 |title=Brendan Foster inducted into Hall of Fame |first=Bill |last=McGuirk |work=[[Evening Chronicle|Newcastle Evening Chronicle]] |date=4 November 2010 |accessdate=16 September 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/north-east-news/evening-chronicle-news/2012/08/28/chronicle-s-100-greatest-geordies-no-s-12-to-10-72703-31711383/2/ |title=Chronicle's 100 Greatest Geordies, Nos 10&ndash;12 |first=Michael |last=Kelly |work=[[Evening Chronicle|Newcastle Evening Chronicle]] |date=28 August 2012 |accessdate=16 September 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120831210752/http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/north-east-news/evening-chronicle-news/2012/08/28/chronicle-s-100-greatest-geordies-no-s-12-to-10-72703-31711383/2/ |archivedate=31 August 2012 }}</ref> Current world triple-jump record holder [[Jonathan Edwards (triple jumper)|Jonathan Edwards]], another member of the England Athletics Hall of Fame,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.englandathletics.org/page.asp?section=847&sectionTitle=Hall+of+Fame+2009+inductees|title=Hall of Fame &ndash; Inductees 2009|publisher=[[England Athletics Hall of Fame]]|year=2009|accessdate=16 September 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120514041704/http://englandathletics.org/page.asp?section=847&sectionTitle=Hall+of+Fame+2009+inductees|archive-date=14 May 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> joined Gateshead Harriers in 1991. Edwards was a member of the club when he set his record mark in [[1995 World Championships in Athletics \u2013 Men's triple jump|winning gold]] at the [[1995 World Championships in Athletics|1995 World Championships]] in Helsinki, when winning [[Athletics at the 2000 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's triple jump|Olympic gold]] at the [[2000 Summer Olympics|2000 Sydney Games]] and a [[2001 World Championships in Athletics \u2013 Men's triple jump|second world title]] a year later in [[Edmonton]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/1477695.stm|title=North east toasts hero Edwards|publisher=[[BBC|the BBC]]|date=7 August 2001|accessdate=16 September 2012}}</ref> Both Foster and Edwards are honorary life members of the club.<ref>Miller, 2008: 173</ref>\n\n===Gateshead Thunder===\n{{main|Newcastle Thunder}}\n[[File:Gateshead vs limoux.jpg|thumb|upright|right|[[Newcastle Thunder|Gateshead Thunder]] playing against Limoux in the [[Challenge Cup]] at Gateshead International Stadium in 2004]]In 1998, Gateshead was awarded a [[rugby league]] franchise after a three-way contest with Cardiff and Swansea. The result was Gateshead Thunder, who played in [[Super League IV]] in 1999.<ref name=\"OFT\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thunderrugby.com/page.php?id=940|title=Club History &ndash; Super League|publisher=Gateshead Thunder|year=2012|accessdate=16 September 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120822071422/http://www.thunderrugby.com/page.php?id=940|archivedate=22 August 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The Thunder played at Gateshead International Stadium and the club had, according to sports journalist Andy Wilson, \"an enjoyable and surprisingly successful season\" which included home and away wins against [[St Helens R.F.C.|St. Helens]] and a sixth-place finish in the table &ndash; missing out on the playoffs by two points.<ref name=\"Guard\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2009/may/29/rugby-league-challenge-cup-gateshead|title=Gateshead Thunder are ready to make a big noise against St Helens|first=Andy|last=Wilson|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=29 May 2009|accessdate=16 September 2012}}</ref> Despite these performances, which attracted an average crowd of 3,895 to Gateshead Stadium, the franchise lost \u00a3700,000 in its first year<ref name=\"OFT\"/> and in November 1999 the [[Rugby Football League]] (RFL) approved a merger with the Hull Sharks.<ref name=\"bbcrfl\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sport/rugby_league/521562.stm|title=Rugby League League's northern empire cut back|publisher=[[BBC|the BBC]]|date=19 November 2012|accessdate=16 September 2012}}</ref> The result was the formation of [[Hull F.C.|Hull FC]], and when the authorities refused permission for the merged clubs to enter a Hull-based team into the RFL's [[Rugby Football League Championship Second Division|second tier]],<ref name=\"OFT\"/> the franchise moved almost in its entirety to Hull, ending Gateshead's Super League participation after a single season; according to Wilson, the Thunder was \"left to die, provoking bitter resentment\" from supporters.<ref name=\"Guard\"/>\n\nAccording to journalist Richard Bott, since the demise of the original Thunder side the club has \"struggled for their very existence.\"<ref name=\"mail\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/rugbyleague/article-1189626/Thorman-keeps-family-Gateshead-skipper-looks-forward-giant-Cup-clash.html|title=Thorman keeps it in the family as Gateshead skipper looks forward to giant Cup clash|first=Richard|last=Bott|work=[[Daily Mail]]|date=29 May 2009|accessdate=16 September 2012}}</ref> There have been some highlights, including winning [[RFL League 1|Championship 1]] in 2008<ref name=\"OFT\"/> and a run to the quarter-final of the [[Challenge Cup]] in 2009 which ended in a 66&ndash;6 defeat to Super League side St Helens in front of 4,325 fans at Gateshead International Stadium.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/rugbyleague/article-1189815/Gateshead-6-St-Helens-66-Saints-march-fourth-Wembley.html|title=Gateshead 6 St Helens 66: Saints march fourth towards Wembley|work=[[Daily Mail]]|date=30 May 2009|accessdate=16 September 2012}}</ref> However, the Thunder went through a 64-game losing streak spanning two-and-a-half years before winning against [[Workington Town]] on 29 August 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/sport/rugby-news/gateshead-thunder/2012/08/30/gateshead-thunder-in-shock-victory-over-visitors-72703-31725698/ |title=Gateshead Thunder in shock victory over visitors |work=[[Evening Chronicle|Newcastle Evening Chronicle]] |date=30 August 2012 |accessdate=16 September 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130119021745/http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/sport/rugby-news/gateshead-thunder/2012/08/30/gateshead-thunder-in-shock-victory-over-visitors-72703-31725698/ |archivedate=19 January 2013 }}</ref>\n\nRelations between the Thunder and Gateshead Council were strained at times, with a possible move to [[Kingston Park (stadium)|Kingston Park]] [[Newcastle upon Tyne]], first mooted, and rejected, in 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sundaysun.co.uk/sport/rugby-north-east/2006/05/10/sights-set-on-top-flight-79310-17055903/|title=Sights set on top flight|first=Jeff|last=Bowron|work=[[Sunday Sun|The Sunday Sun]]|date=10 May 2006|accessdate=16 September 2012}}</ref> In 2008, the club committed itself again to Gateshead Stadium for the immediate future,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/2008/10/30/thunder-agree-deal-to-continue-playing-at-stadium-72703-22150967/|title=Thunder agree deal to continue playing at Stadium|first=Nick|last=Purewal|work=[[Evening Chronicle|Newcastle Evening Chronicle]]|date=30 October 2008|accessdate=16 September 2012}}</ref> however, in March 2014 [[The Journal (newspaper)|The Journal]] reported that talks had begun between Thunder's managing director Keith Christie and representatives of [[Newcastle Falcons]] with a view to the Falcons taking over the rugby league club.<ref>{{cite book|title=Newcastle Falcons set to take over Newcastle Thunder|url=http://www.thejournal.co.uk/sport/rugby-union/newcastle-falcons-set-take-over-6772996|work=[[The Journal (newspaper)|The Journal]]|first=Mark|last=Smith|date=5 March 2014|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref> Falcons' owner Semore Kurdi confirmed that a bid had been made to purchase Gateshead Thunder on 20 March 2014, though he refused to elaborate on whether he intended to relocate the club if that bid was accepted.<ref>{{cite book|title=Newcastle Falcons confirm bid to buy Gateshead Thunder|url=http://www.thejournal.co.uk/sport/rugby-union/newcastle-falcons-confirm-bid-buy-6854075|work=[[The Journal (newspaper)|The Journal]]|first=Mark|last=Smith|date=20 March 2014|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref> The takeover was confirmed on 23 May 2014, though it was announced that the club would continue to play at the International Stadium.<ref>{{cite book|title=Newcastle Falcons unite rugby codes in Gateshead Thunder takeover|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/sport/other-sport/rugby-league/newcastle-falcons-unite-rugby-codes-7162734|work=[[Evening Chronicle]]|first=Mark|last=Smith|date=23 May 2014|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref> In January 2015 Gateshead Thunder were officially renamed Newcastle Thunder and relocated to Kingston Park. Keith Christie told the BBC that the move was \"a business decision\" designed to build a new fan base for the club.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-league/30901286|title=Newcastle Thunder: Gateshead rugby league side relocates|publisher=[[BBC|The BBC]]|date=20 January 2015|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Gateshead Senators===\n{{main|Gateshead Senators}}\nThe [[Gateshead Senators]] (originally the Gateshead International Senators) are an [[American football]] club formed in 1988 when the Newcastle Senators, who played at Northern Rugby Club, moved across the Tyne to play at the Gateshead International Stadium.<ref name=\"SenHistory\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gateshead-senators.com/history.html|title=Gateshead Senators &ndash; History|publisher=Gateshead&ndash;Senators.com|year=2012|accessdate=15 September 2012}}</ref> The club has had mixed fortunes but their most successful season came in 1999. Having won eight of their nine games in the regular season, the team won the Division One North title and advanced to the end-of-season playoffs. After beating the Merseyside Nighthawks 43&ndash;0 in the quarter-finals, the Senators defeated the [[Essex Spartans]] 33&ndash;19 in the semi-finals to reach the championship final. At the [[Saffron Lane sports centre|Saffron Lane Stadium]] in [[Leicester]], the Senators faced the [[Bristol Aztecs (American football)|Bristol Aztecs]]. In a tight encounter, the Senators claimed the Division One [[British American Football League]] title with a 7&ndash;2 victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.users.zetnet.co.uk/pcrrn/senators/final99.htm|title=Gateshead Senators Division One Champions|publisher=[[Gateshead Senators]]|year=1999|accessdate=17 November 2012}} This site is a redirect from the official history links provided on the Gateshead Senators website.</ref> The club reached the playoffs again in the next three seasons but were unable to replicate that success, and after a season voluntarily spent in Division Two in 2003, returned to Division One North in 2004. They continue to play in that division, and in the 2012 season failed to make the playoffs after recording five wins and five defeats in their ten games.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bafanl.co.uk/team/18 |title=Gateshead Senators |publisher=[[BAFA National Leagues|British American Football National League]] |year=2012 |accessdate=17 November 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130126004959/http://www.bafanl.co.uk/team/18 |archivedate=26 January 2013 }}</ref>\n\nThe Senators were a tenant at Gateshead Stadium from 1988 to 2011.<ref name=\"SenHistory\"/> In 2012, the club announced plans to move away from Gateshead for the start of the 2012 season to create \"a better game-day experience\" and they now play at the [[Monkton Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Grounds+for+optimism+over+Senators%27+switch%3B+AMERICAN+FOOTBALL.-a0277972301|title=Grounds for optimism over Senators switch|work=[[Evening Chronicle|Newcastle Evening Chronicle]]|date=25 January 2012|accessdate=22 December 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Concert venue==\n\nGateshead International Stadium has been used for many years as a concert venue.<ref>{{cite news|title=Gebrselassie set to star at Gateshead|first=Alan|last=Pattullo|work=[[The Scotsman]]|date=2 June 1999}}</ref> On 31 July 1982, [[The Police]] performed at the stadium as part of their [[Ghost in the Machine Tour]], with [[U2]] as a supporting act. Reports in the local press suggested that The Police seemed disappointed that the stadium was only half full and cited high ticket prices and poor weather as possible causes.<ref>{{cite news|title=Lukewarm greeting as hero returns|first=Bill|last=Brown|work=[[The Journal (newspaper)|The Journal]]|date=1 August 1982}}</ref> On 16 June 1992 [[Guns N' Roses]], supported by [[Soundgarden]] and [[Faith No More]], performed at the stadium. This time the weather was hot and sunny which helped ensure that the concert, part of the [[Use Your Illusion Tour]], was a sell-out.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/2012/05/11/interview-dizzy-reed-ahead-of-guns-n-roses-gig-72703-30948744/ |title=Interview: Dizzy Reed ahead of Guns N' Roses gig |first=Mick |last=Burgess |work=[[Evening Chronicle|Newcastle Evening Chronicle]] |date=11 May 2012 |accessdate=9 November 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120513135831/http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/2012/05/11/interview-dizzy-reed-ahead-of-guns-n-roses-gig-72703-30948744/ |archivedate=13 May 2012 }}</ref> American rock group [[Bon Jovi]] have played twice at the stadium. The first occasion was on 27 June 1995, while supported by [[Skin (British band)|Skin]], on their [[These Days Tour]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/multimedia/entertainment/2012/10/30/flashback-bon-jovi-play-the-gateshead-stadium-72703-32129039/#2 |title=Flashback: Bon Jovi play the Gateshead Stadium |work=[[Evening Chronicle|Newcastle Evening Chronicle]] |date=30 October 2012 |accessdate=9 November 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130201182841/http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/multimedia/entertainment/2012/10/30/flashback-bon-jovi-play-the-gateshead-stadium-72703-32129039/ |archivedate=1 February 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skinfreak.co.uk/biography|title=Biography|publisher=Skin: The Official Website|year=2012|accessdate=9 November 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105225131/http://www.skinfreak.co.uk/biography|archive-date=5 November 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The group returned to Gateshead on 22 August 2000 as part of their [[Crush Tour]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/893047.stm|title=Bon Jovi delights British fans|publisher=[[BBC|the BBC]]|date=23 August 2000|accessdate=9 November 2012}}</ref> Another artist who has performed multiple times at Gateshead International Stadium is [[Tina Turner]]. As part of her [[Foreign Affair: The Farewell Tour]], Turner performed twice on consecutive nights (21&ndash;22 July 1990) and attracted a total of 60,000 spectators.<ref>Welch, 1995: 192</ref> Turner performed for a third time at the stadium as part of her [[Wildest Dreams Tour]] on 12 July 1996.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/TINA.-a061156467|title=Tina|first=Lisa|last=Burrows|work=[[The People]]|date=26 May 1996|accessdate=22 December 2012}}</ref> Most recently the venue played host to [[Little Mix]] on 26 July 2018 as part of their [[Summer Hits Tour 2018|Summer Hits Tour]]. Other artists to have played at the stadium include [[Bryan Adams]], [[Rod Stewart]], [[Simple Minds]] and [[Simply Red]].<ref>{{cite news|title=A billion fans bowl star over |first=Sonia |last=Sharma |work=[[Evening Chronicle|Newcastle Evening Chronicle]] |date=27 January 2003 |page=12}}</ref>\n\n==Transport==\n\n[[File:Gateshead Stadium Metro Station - geograph.org.uk - 70792.jpg|thumb|[[Gateshead Stadium Metro station]]]]\nGateshead International Stadium is {{convert|2|mi|km|0}} east of Gateshead Town Centre and is on the [[A184 road (England)#Triple-digit roads|A184 Felling Bypass]], with access to a car park at Neilson Road.<ref>Report to Cabinet &ndash; Gateshead International Stadium &ndash; Draft Development Brief, 2010: 7 at para.15</ref> Journey time by car from Gateshead town centre is approximately five minutes and a further five minutes travel from Newcastle upon Tyne.<ref>Using Gateshead International Stadium as reference points. See {{cite web|url=http://www.simplygo.com/download/publication/42497.52|title=The Loop: Timetable|publisher=[[Go North East]]|date=29 July 2012|accessdate=22 December 2012}}</ref> A footpath runs adjacent to the Felling bypass and the journey by foot from Gateshead town centre takes some fifteen minutes. A journey east to [[Heworth Interchange]] also takes around fifteen minutes. Two designated cycle routes run past the stadium. These are [[National Cycle Route 72|Hadrian's Way]], which provides access from [[Tynemouth]] in the east and [[Wylam]] in the west, and the [[National Cycle Route 14|Keelman's Way]], which runs along the south bank of the [[River Tyne]] towards [[Blaydon-on-Tyne]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gateshead.ac.uk/media/15274/academy_for_sport_travel_guide.pdf|title=How to get to the Academy for Sport at Gateshead International Stadium|publisher=[[Gateshead College]]|year=2012|accessdate=26 September 2012}} at p.1</ref>\n\nThe stadium is well served by public transport. It has its own [[Tyne and Wear Metro]] station, the [[Gateshead Stadium Metro station]]. This is at Shelley Drive, some five minutes' walk from the ground.<ref name=\"sport2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gateshead.ac.uk/media/15274/academy_for_sport_travel_guide.pdf|title=How to get to the Academy for Sport at Gateshead International Stadium|publisher=[[Gateshead College]]|year=2012|accessdate=26 September 2012}} at p.2</ref> Trains run direct from this station to all other Metro destinations; trains to [[South Shields Metro station|South Shields]] and [[South Hylton metro station|South Hylton]] stop at platform one while trains travelling towards [[St James Metro station|St James]] and [[Airport Metro station (Tyne and Wear)|Airport]] stop at platform two.<ref name=\"metro\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nexus.org.uk/metro/timetables/gateshead-stadium |title=Metro Stations: Gateshead Stadium |publisher=[[Tyne and Wear Passenger Transport Executive]] |date=July 2012 |accessdate=22 December 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100617165914/http://www.nexus.org.uk/metro/timetables/gateshead-stadium |archivedate=17 June 2010 }}</ref> The Gateshead Stadium Metro station is open seven days a week<ref name=\"metro\"/> and at peak times seventeen trains per hour stop there.<ref name=\"sport2\"/> The nearest mainline railway station is [[Newcastle railway station|Newcastle Central Station]], around {{convert|3|mi|km|0}} away, though local rail travel calls at Heworth Interchange.<ref name=\"sport2\"/> [[Go North East]] operate the 93/4 \"Loop\" bus service, which provides access to the stadium from the [[Team Valley]], [[Gateshead Interchange]], Heworth Interchange and [[Queen Elizabeth Hospital, Gateshead|Queen Elizabeth Hospital]] in [[Sheriff Hill]]. This bus runs every fifteen minutes during the day and every half-hour during evenings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.simplygo.com/download/publication/5870.28|title=Route Map: Loop|publisher=[[Go North East]]|year=2012|accessdate=26 September 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=nb}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2016}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{Commons category|Gateshead Stadium}}\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://online.gateshead.gov.uk/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-26070/Item+15a+-+Gateshead+International+Stadium+%28GIS%29+%E2%80%93+Revised+Draft+Development+Brief.pdf|title=Report to Cabinet &ndash; Gateshead International Stadium &ndash; Draft Development Brief|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111002120533/http://online.gateshead.gov.uk/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-26070/Item+15a+-+Gateshead+International+Stadium+(GIS)+%E2%80%93+Revised+Draft+Development+Brief.pdf|archivedate=2 October 2011|publisher=Gateshead MBC|date=25 May 2010|accessdate=28 December 2012}}\n*{{cite book |title=File on Felling|first=Joan |last=Hewitt |publisher=Gateshead Central Library |year=1990}}\n*{{cite book |title=A Topographical Dictionary of England|url=https://archive.org/details/topographicaldic00lewi2|first=Samuel |last=Lewis|publisher=Lewis|year=1848}}\n*{{cite book |title=Top distance runners of the Century|first=Seppo |last=Luhtala|publisher=Mayer & Mayer Verlag|year=2002}}\n*{{cite book |title=Paralympian, My Autobiography|first=Stephen |last=Miller|publisher=Tonto Books|year=2008}}\n*{{cite book |title=Urban Regeneration|first=Thomas|last=Telford|publisher=The Institute of Civil Engineers|year=1988}}\n*{{cite book |title=The Brewing Grade Review |last=Unknown |publisher=Brewers' Society, London|year=1961}} \n*{{cite book |title=The Tina Turner Experience|first=Chris |last=Welch |publisher=Virgin |year=1995}}\n{{refend}}\n{{Gateshead F.C.}}\n{{Conference National Venues}}\n{{1995 RLWC Venues}}\n{{2000 RLWC Venues}}\n{{featured article}}\n\n[[Category:Athletics (track and field) venues in England]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Gateshead]]\n[[Category:Football venues in England]]\n[[Category:Gateshead F.C.]]\n[[Category:Gateshead A.F.C.]]\n[[Category:Gateshead United F.C.]]\n[[Category:Rugby league stadiums in England]]\n[[Category:Rugby League World Cup stadiums]]\n[[Category:Sports venues in Tyne and Wear]]\n[[Category:Sports venues completed in 1955]]\n[[Category:Sport in Gateshead]]\n[[Category:1955 establishments in the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{featured article}}\n{{EngvarB|date=May 2014}}\n{{Infobox venue\n| stadium_name      = Gateshead International Stadium \n| logo_image        = \n| logo_caption      =\n| image             = [[File:Gateshead Stadium - geograph-1116309.jpg|250px|entrance]]\n| caption           = Main entrance to the stadium\n| fullname          = Gateshead International Stadium\n| former_names      = Gateshead Youth Stadium\n| location          = Neilson Road<br>[[Gateshead]]<br>[[Tyne and Wear]]<br>NE10 0EF\n| coordinates       = {{coord|54|57|40|N|1|34|47|W|display=inline,title}}\n| broke_ground      = 1955\n| built             = 1955\n| opened            = 27 August 1955\n| renovated         = 1974\n| expanded          = 2010\n| owner             = [[Gateshead Council#Local government|Gateshead Metropolitan Borough Council]]\n| operator          = Gateshead Metropolitan Borough Council\n| surface           = Synthetic running track, grass inner\n| scoreboard        = Yes &ndash; by HS Sports<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hssports.co.uk/displays-scoreboards/references?page=3|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151230111839/http://www.hssports.co.uk/displays-scoreboards/led-screen-scoreboard-references?page=3|archivedate=30 December 2015|title=HS Sports: references|publisher=HS Sports|year=2012|accessdate=9 November 2012}}</ref>\n| cost              = Originally \u00a330,000 (1955)<ref name=\"gateshead1\"/>\n| capacity          = 11,800\n| record_attendance = 14,797 (sports),<ref name=\"McGuirk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/sport/athletics-news/2009/08/27/gateshead-stadium-still-a-world-beater-venue-72703-24537934/|title=Gateshead Stadium still a world-beater venue|first=Bill|last=McGuirk|work=[[Newcastle Evening Chronicle]]|date=27 August 2009|accessdate=9 September 2012}}</ref> 30,000 (various concerts)\n| dimensions        = {{convert|100|x|64|m|yd|1}}\n| acreage           = 24.4 hectares\n| tenants           = [[Gateshead A.F.C.]] (1973)<br>[[Gateshead United F.C.|Gateshead United]] (1974\u20131977)<br/>[[Gateshead F.C.]] (1977\u2013present)<br>[[Gateshead Harriers]] (1956&ndash;present)<br/>[[Gateshead Senators]] (1988&ndash;2012)<br/>[[Gateshead Thunder (1999)|Gateshead Thunder]] (1999)<br>[[Newcastle Thunder|Gateshead Thunder]] (2001&ndash;2014)\n|}}\n'''Gateshead International Stadium (GIS)''' is a [[multi-purpose stadium|multi-purpose]], [[all-seater]] venue in [[Gateshead]], Tyne and Wear, England. Originally known as the '''Gateshead Youth Stadium''', the venue was built in 1955 at a cost of \u00a330,000. It has since been extensively re-developed on three occasions. Its capacity of around 11,800{{refn|group=nb|This is the most widely quoted figure, but at least one council document provides a figure of 11,750.<ref name=\"Quinn\">{{cite web|url=http://online.gateshead.gov.uk/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-23427/Item+09+-+Delivery+of+the+Redevelopment+of+Gateshead+International+Stadium+report.doc |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140513235645/http://online.gateshead.gov.uk/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-23427/Item%2B09%2B-%2BDelivery%2Bof%2Bthe%2BRedevelopment%2Bof%2BGateshead%2BInternational%2BStadium%2Breport.doc |archivedate=13 May 2014 |title=Report to Cabinet &ndash; Delivery of the Redevelopment of Gateshead International Stadium |first=Derek |last=Quinn |publisher=Gateshead MBC |date=27 January 2009 |accessdate=28 December 2012 |url-status=dead }} at p.3</ref>}} is the greatest in the [[Metropolitan Borough of Gateshead]], the third-largest in Tyne and Wear (behind only [[St James' Park]] and the [[Stadium of Light]]) and the sixth-largest in [[North East England]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldstadiums.com/europe/countries/united_kingdom/england/north_east.shtml|title=Stadiums in North East England|publisher=World Stadiums|year=2012|accessdate=9 November 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120622114318/http://www.worldstadiums.com/europe/countries/united_kingdom/england/north_east.shtml|archivedate=22 June 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe main arena is principally used for athletics. The inaugural athletics competition at the redeveloped venue, the 1974 \"Gateshead Games\", was instigated by [[Brendan Foster]], a Gateshead Council employee at that time. By breaking the world record in the [[3000 metres|men's 3,000&nbsp;m]], Foster brought international publicity to the new stadium and began a tradition of athletics competitions at the venue, which has since hosted the [[British Grand Prix (athletics)|British Grand Prix]] (2003&ndash;10) and the [[European Team Championships]] in 1989, 2000 and 2013. It is the only venue to have hosted the latter event three times. Five world records have been set at the stadium, including two by [[pole vault]]er [[Yelena Isinbayeva]] and a tied [[100 metres]] record by [[Asafa Powell]] in 2006.\n\nAlthough the venue primarily caters for athletics, it is the current or former home to teams in several sports. It has been used by the town's main football club since 1971. Gateshead International Stadium was home to the [[Gateshead Thunder (1999)|Gateshead Thunder]] [[rugby league]] club during their spell in the [[Super League]] and the replacement [[Newcastle Thunder|Gateshead Thunder club]] played home games in the main arena, which was known as the '''Thunderdome''' when used by that team<ref>{{cite web|title=Gateshead Thunder end two-and-a-half-year wait for win|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/rugby-league/19422254|publisher=[[BBC|the BBC]]|date=30 August 2012|accessdate=18 January 2013}}</ref> until the club relocated to Newcastle in 2015. Gateshead Harriers Athletic Club, which includes Foster and [[Jonathan Edwards (triple jumper)|Jonathan Edwards]] among its life members, are the oldest tenants, having used the site since 1956. The stadium has also been used as a concert venue by numerous musical artists including [[Little Mix]], [[Guns N' Roses]], [[Bon Jovi]], [[Bryan Adams]] and [[Tina Turner]].\n\n==History and development==\n\nThe stadium is built on the site of two large chemical works opened in 1827 and 1834.<ref name=\"chroniclelive1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/communities/felling/2012/01/01/ten-interesting-facts-about-felling-72703-30939585/ |title=Ten interesting facts about Felling |work=[[Evening Chronicle|Newcastle Evening Chronicle]] |date=1 January 2012 |accessdate=28 August 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130202093036/http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/communities/felling/2012/01/01/ten-interesting-facts-about-felling-72703-30939585/ |archivedate=2 February 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>Lewis, 1848: 227</ref> These works initially thrived, but by the early part of the 20th century both were in terminal decline,<ref>Hewitt (part three), 1990: 1 at para. 5</ref> and were demolished in 1932 to leave behind a 2-million-tonne heap of spoil.<ref name=\"chroniclelive1\"/><ref name=\"DB8\">Report to Cabinet &ndash; Gateshead International Stadium &ndash; Draft Development Brief, 2010: 8</ref> This land, approximately {{convert|2|mi}} east of the centre of Gateshead,<ref>Report to Cabinet &ndash; Gateshead International Stadium &ndash; Draft Development Brief, 2010: 7</ref> was cleared in 1942 but continued to lie derelict until the mid-1950s.<ref name=\"DB8\"/>\n\nIn early 1955, Gateshead Council began work on transforming this land. The Gateshead Youth Stadium, built on the site of the old chemical works, was opened by [[Jim Peters (athlete)|Jim Peters]] on 27 August 1955.<ref name=\"gateshead1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gateshead2013.com/thevenue.html|title=The Venue &ndash; Gateshead International Stadium|publisher=Gateshead Council|year=2013|accessdate=19 January 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121215061336/http://www.gateshead2013.com/thevenue.html|archivedate=15 December 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Costing \u00a330,000, the original venue contained little more than a cinder running track and an asphalt cycling track, though floodlights and a seating area were added soon after.<ref name=\"gateshead1\"/> On 1&nbsp;July 1961, the arena hosted its first major competition\u2014the [[Vaux Breweries]] International Athletics Meet<ref name=\"BGR\">''The Brewing Grade Review'', 1961: 922</ref>\u2014but according to sportswriter John Gibson, the Youth Stadium remained \"little more than a minor track with a tiny grandstand and open terraces\".<ref name=\"ICN\">{{cite web|url=http://icnewcastle.icnetwork.co.uk/0200sport/0600athletics/tm_objectid=14208798%26method=full%26siteid=50081%26headline=face-to-face--brendan-foster-name_page.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151230110849/http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/sport/other-sport/face-to-face-brendan-foster-1615997|archivedate=30 December 2015|title=Face to Face: Brendan Foster|first=John|last=Gibson|work=[[Newcastle Evening Chronicle]]|date=4 May 2004|accessdate=28 December 2012}} at p.2</ref>\n\n[[File:Gateshead 1975.jpg|thumb|left|Aerial photograph of Gateshead (1975). The rebuilt stadium is prominent (top centre).]]According to author Thomas Telfer, by the turn of the 1970s, the town of Gateshead was suffering from \"the classic symptoms of decay in its inner-city areas\". The response during the 1960s had been a programme of systematic derelict land reclamation and environmental improvement.<ref>Telford, 1988: 79</ref> While these measures did not have an immediate positive impact on the perception of the town, Gateshead Council pressed ahead by looking to develop existing infrastructure with a view to overall regeneration.<ref>Telford, 1988: 80</ref> One such opportunity was identified at the Gateshead Youth Stadium, where the council believed that investment might raise the region's profile and bring international recognition.<ref>Moore, Fox and Elliot, 2003: 107</ref> In April 1974, Gateshead Council inaugurated a \"Sport and Recreation\" department.<ref name=\"ICN\"/> In July 1974, the council appointed [[Brendan Foster]]\u2014a former schoolteacher turned athlete and a native of [[Tyne and Wear]]\u2014as the Council's sport and recreation manager.<ref name=\"Gibson 2004:1\"/><ref name=\"Freedom\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/tyne/3761364.stm|title=Foster given Freedom of Gateshead|publisher=the BBC|date=20 October 2004|accessdate=29 August 2012}}</ref> Foster, who according to Gibson became \"the father of Gateshead athletics\",<ref name=\"Gibson 2004:1\">{{cite web|url=http://icnewcastle.icnetwork.co.uk/0200sport/0600athletics/tm_objectid=14208798%26method=full%26siteid=50081%26headline=face-to-face--brendan-foster-name_page.html|title=Face to Face: Brendan Foster|first=John|last=Gibson|work=[[Newcastle Evening Chronicle]]|date=4 May 2004|accessdate=28 December 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151230110849/http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/sport/other-sport/face-to-face-brendan-foster-1615997|archivedate=30 December 2015}} at p.1</ref> had been forced to train in [[Edinburgh]] during 1973 as a result of the poor condition of the Youth Stadium track.<ref name=\"UKA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.uka.org.uk/e-inspire/hall-of-fame-athletes/brendan-foster/|title=Brendan Foster|publisher=[[UK Athletics]]|year=2011|accessdate=29 August 2012}}</ref> In December 1973, he had been invited to a civic reception to celebrate his breaking of the two-mile world record earlier that year at Crystal Palace. At this reception, Foster was told that a new [[all-weather running track|synthetic track]] was being laid at Gateshead Youth Stadium. His response was a promise that, if the Council was serious, he would run at the stadium and break a world record (Foster later offered an explanation of that promise: \"You know how it is when you've had a few drinks&mdash;you promise the world!\").<ref name=\"ICN\"/> When the track was laid in early&nbsp;1974, Foster became convinced of the Council's sincerity.<ref name=\"ICN\"/> He was interviewed for the managerial position<ref name=\"ICN\"/> and, upon appointment, became the \"driving force\"<ref name=\"Freedom\"/> behind the programme of improvements to the Youth Stadium, which included the building of the main, covered Tyne and Wear stand in 1980<ref name=\"blue\"/> and three accompanying stands; the venue was renamed the Gateshead International Stadium.<ref name=\"gateshead1\"/><ref name=\"Freedom\"/> This first tranche of improvements cost around \u00a38&nbsp;million,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/history/domesday/dblock/GB-424000-561000/page/2|title=Domesday Reloaded: Gateshead International Stadium|publisher=[[BBC|the BBC]]|year=2011|accessdate=29 August 2012}}</ref> and Foster's proposal to commemorate the re-opening with an athletic event was approved, allowing for the first \"Gateshead Games\" to be held in 1974.<ref name=\"Gibson 2004:1\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1090986/2/index.htm|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151230112654/http://www.si.com/vault/1976/04/19/614810/howay-big-bren-yere-doin-us-prood|archivedate=30 December 2015|title=Howay, Big Bren! Ye're doin' us prood!|work=[[Sports Illustrated]]|first=Ray|last=Kennedy|date=19 April 1976|accessdate=8 March 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Tyne and wear stand.jpg|thumb|Young athletes run past the Tyne and Wear stand at Gateshead International Stadium]]The success of the first Gateshead Games, and their subsequent annual renewal, raised the profile of the stadium and caused Gateshead Council to further their financial investment. During the 1980s, additions were made to the site infrastructure, including the building of an indoor sports hall, outdoor football pitches and a gymnasium.<ref name=\"gateshead1\"/> In 1989 the running track was again relaid<ref name=\"TrackDir\"/> and Gateshead confirmed its reputation as a top-class athletics venue by hosting the [[European Cup (athletics)|Europa Cup]] (forerunner to the [[European Team Championships]]).<ref name=\"Europa1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/athletics/3007647/Athletics-Gateshead-glory-had-invigorating-effect.html|title=Gateshead glory had invigorating effect|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|last=Knight|first=Tom|date=20 June 2001|accessdate=31 August 2012}}</ref> In the 21st century, the site has been the subject of two major re-development projects. The first was completed in 2006, when two artificial outdoor football pitches, indoor athletic training facilities, sports science provisions and conferencing rooms were added at a cost of \u00a315&nbsp;million.<ref name=\"pitch up\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gateshead.gov.uk/Council%20and%20Democracy/news/News%20Articles/PITCH%20UP%20AT%20GATESHEAD%20INTERNATIONAL%20STADIUM.aspx|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060707180931/http://www.gateshead.gov.uk/Council%20and%20Democracy/news/News%20Articles/PITCH%20UP%20AT%20GATESHEAD%20INTERNATIONAL%20STADIUM.aspx|archivedate=7 July 2006|title=Pitch up at Gateshead International Stadium|publisher=Gateshead Council|date=27 June 2006|accessdate=31 August 2012}}</ref> The revamped stadium, funded by collaboration between [[One NorthEast]], [[Sport England]] and [[Gateshead College]] among others, was opened on 12 May 2006 by [[Sebastian Coe]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gateshead.gov.uk/Council%20and%20Democracy/news/News%20Articles/Lord%20Coe%20Opens%20New%20Development%20at%20Gateshead%20International%20Stadium.aspx |archive-url=https://archive.is/20121223155726/http://www.gateshead.gov.uk/Council%20and%20Democracy/news/News%20Articles/Lord%20Coe%20Opens%20New%20Development%20at%20Gateshead%20International%20Stadium.aspx |url-status=dead |archive-date=23 December 2012 |title=Lord Coe opens new development at Gateshead International Stadium |publisher=Gateshead Council |date=12 May 2006 |accessdate=31 August 2012 }}</ref>\n\nA second tranche of development, undertaken in two stages, was approved in November 2009.<ref name=\"Richards\">{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/north-east-news/evening-chronicle-news/2009/11/04/plans-to-revamp-gateshead-stadium-unveiled-72703-25089463/|title=Plans to revamp Gateshead Stadium unveiled |first=Linda|last=Richards|work=[[Evening Chronicle|Newcastle Evening Chronicle]]|date=4 November 2009|accessdate=31 August 2012}}</ref> This included a general refurbishment and improvement of the existing facilities at the stadium, adding cover, better toilet and new refreshment facilities to the exposed East Stand, improving wheelchair access, adding extra catering and conferencing facilities and a new media and management centre.<ref name=\"ALee\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gateshead.gov.uk/Leisure%20and%20Culture/sports1/news/development/GIS.aspx|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110213062619/http://www.gateshead.gov.uk/Leisure%20and%20Culture/sports1/news/development/GIS.aspx|archivedate=13 February 2011|title=Development Plans: Gateshead International Stadium|first=A|last=Lee|publisher=Gateshead Council|year=2010|accessdate=31 August 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"DB5\">Report to Cabinet &ndash; Gateshead International Stadium &ndash; Draft Development Brief, 2010: 5</ref> This was funded by collaboration between Gateshead Council, local development funds and Gateshead College.<ref name=\"ALee\"/> The covering of the 4,000-seat<ref name=\"Richards\"/> East Stand with a new canopy roof<ref>{{cite web|url=http://online.gateshead.gov.uk/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-27570/Item+06+-+Gateshead+International+Stadium+-+Tender+report.doc|archive-url=http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20111002092650/http://online.gateshead.gov.uk/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document%2D27570/Item%2B06%2B%2D%2BGateshead%2BInternational%2BStadium%2B%2D%2BTender%2Breport.doc|url-status=dead|archive-date=2 October 2011|title=Report to cabinet &ndash; Gateshead International Stadium (GIS) &ndash; Main Arena Tender|first=Dowling|last=Paul|publisher=Gateshead MBC|date=20 July 2010|accessdate= 28 December 2012}} at p.1</ref> was completed in July 2010, immediately prior to Gateshead hosting a [[2010 IAAF Diamond League|Diamond League]] event.<ref name=\"covered\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gateshead.gov.uk/Council%20and%20Democracy/news/News%20Articles/GatesheadInternationalStadiumimprovements.aspx|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110918124501/http://www.gateshead.gov.uk/Council%20and%20Democracy/news/News%20Articles/GatesheadInternationalStadiumimprovements.aspx|archivedate=18 September 2011|title=Gateshead International Stadium Improvements; Spectators to be covered in glory in time for sprinting champions head to head |publisher=Gateshead Council|date=12 July 2010|accessdate=31 August 2012}}</ref> The second stage of the re-development\u2014the building of the corporate and media facilities\u2014commenced on 6&nbsp;September 2010 and was completed on time in summer&nbsp;2011.<ref name=\"ALee\"/> The total cost of the work was estimated to be \u00a37.6&nbsp;million.<ref name=\"DB5\"/>\n\nA third programme of expansion was initially mooted in 2008. The aim of this programme was to expand the stadium into an all-embracing \"sports village\",<ref>Report to Cabinet &ndash; Gateshead International Stadium &ndash; Draft Development Brief, 2010: 3</ref> replete with an ice rink, indoor golf course, restaurants and shops. Gateshead Council invited tenders in August 2008 from commercial organisations interested in undertaking the development.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/tyne/7579943.stm|title=Ice arena plan at sports stadium|publisher=BBC|date=24 August 2008|accessdate=31 August 2012}}</ref> A formal draft development brief was compiled and published in November 2009.<ref>Report to Cabinet &ndash; Gateshead International Stadium &ndash; Draft Development Brief, 2010</ref> A report to Council in December 2009 noted that there had been \"a reasonable level of interest at the preliminary stage\" from private investors, but that only one detailed proposal had been submitted, which had been declined by the Council on financial grounds.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://online.gateshead.gov.uk/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-26069/Item+15+-+Gateshead+International+Stadium+(GIS)+%E2%80%93+Revised+Draft+Development+Brief+report.doc|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111002120617/http://online.gateshead.gov.uk/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-26069/Item+15+-+Gateshead+International+Stadium+%28GIS%29+%E2%80%93+Revised+Draft+Development+Brief+report.doc|url-status=dead|archive-date=2 October 2011|title=Gateshead International Stadium (GIS) &ndash; Revised Draft Development Brief|first=Derek|last=Quinn|publisher=Gateshead MBC|date=15 December 2009|accessdate=28 December 2012}} at p.1</ref> The report also noted concerns that the original centrepiece of the proposed village, the ice rink, may have been deterring investors and that a similar proposal to redevelop land at the [[Stadium of Light]] in [[Sunderland, Tyne and Wear|Sunderland]] was detracting from what councillors had hoped to be a unique feature of the proposed village.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://online.gateshead.gov.uk/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-26069/Item+15+-+Gateshead+International+Stadium+(GIS)+%E2%80%93+Revised+Draft+Development+Brief+report.doc|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111002120617/http://online.gateshead.gov.uk/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-26069/Item+15+-+Gateshead+International+Stadium+%28GIS%29+%E2%80%93+Revised+Draft+Development+Brief+report.doc|url-status=dead|archive-date=2 October 2011|title=Gateshead International Stadium (GIS) &ndash; Revised Draft Development Brief|first=Derek|last=Quinn|publisher=Gateshead MBC|date=15 December 2009|accessdate=28 December 2012}} at p.7</ref> The result was that a fresh proposal was raised to remove the ice rink from the brief in an attempt to \"stimulate the market\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://online.gateshead.gov.uk/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-26069/Item+15+-+Gateshead+International+Stadium+(GIS)+%E2%80%93+Revised+Draft+Development+Brief+report.doc|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111002120617/http://online.gateshead.gov.uk/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-26069/Item+15+-+Gateshead+International+Stadium+%28GIS%29+%E2%80%93+Revised+Draft+Development+Brief+report.doc|url-status=dead|archive-date=2 October 2011|title=Gateshead International Stadium (GIS) &ndash; Revised Draft Development Brief|first=Derek|last=Quinn|publisher=Gateshead MBC|date=15 December 2009|accessdate=28 December 2012}} at p.8</ref> A public consultation was undertaken and in May 2010 the council reported that 327 of the 375 responses received were in favour of the amended proposal.<ref name=\"Dowling\">{{cite web|url=http://online.gateshead.gov.uk/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-27194/Item+10+-1-+Gateshead+International+Stadium+(GIS)+%E2%80%93+Development+Brief+report.doc|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111002102429/http://online.gateshead.gov.uk/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-27194/Item+10+-1-+Gateshead+International+Stadium+%28GIS%29+%E2%80%93+Development+Brief+report.doc|url-status=dead|archive-date=2 October 2011|title=Report to cabinet &ndash; Gateshead International Stadium (GIS) &ndash; Development Brief|first=Dowling|last=Paul|publisher=Gateshead MBC|date=25 May 2010|accessdate=28 December 2012}} at p.1</ref> As a result, notice was given to developers that the council intended to market the site and ten responses were received.<ref name=\"Dowling\"/>\n\n==Structure and facilities==\n\n[[File:Gateshead International Stadium Layout.png|thumb|Diagram demonstrating layout of main arena at Gateshead International Stadium<ref name=\"UKA Aviva\"/>]]Gateshead International Stadium and its facilities occupy {{convert|24.4|ha|acre}} of land.<ref>Report to Cabinet &ndash; Gateshead International Stadium &ndash; Draft Development Brief, 2010: 7 at para.17</ref> The main athletics arena at Gateshead International Stadium is an [[All-seater stadium|all-seater]], bowl-shaped arena consisting of four stands of seats.<ref name=\"blue\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bluesqfootball.com/story/0,20970,13036_3770978,00.html |title=Gateshead |publisher=Bluesquarefootball.com |year=2012 |accessdate=26 September 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121018180435/http://www.bluesqfootball.com/story/0%2C20970%2C13036_3770978%2C00.html |archivedate=18 October 2012 }}</ref> The precise capacity of the venue is uncertain; some sources claim it to be 11,750,<ref name=\"Quinn\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gateshead-fc.com/gateshead-international-stadium |title=Gateshead International Stadium |publisher=[[Gateshead F.C.]] |year=2012 |accessdate=26 September 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120801005617/http://www.gateshead-fc.com/gateshead-international-stadium |archivedate=1 August 2012 }}</ref> others 11,762<ref name=\"TrackDir\"/> and some provide a figure of 11,800.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thunderrugby.com/page.php?id=970|title=Gateshead International Stadium&nbsp;- Home of Thunder|publisher=[[Newcastle Thunder|Gateshead Thunder]]|year=2012|accessdate=26 September 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120707171821/http://www.thunderrugby.com/page.php?id=970|archivedate=7 July 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gateshead-fc.com/4125/media-watch-grounds-for-hope-over-new-gateshead-fc-stadium |title=Media Watch &ndash; Grounds for hope over new Gateshead FC stadium |first=Steve |last=Brown |publisher=[[Gateshead F.C.]] |date=23 August 2012 |accessdate=26 September 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120926044906/http://www.gateshead-fc.com/4125/media-watch-grounds-for-hope-over-new-gateshead-fc-stadium |archivedate=26 September 2012 }}</ref> The main stand is the Tyne and Wear Stand, a steep, [[cantilever]]ed structure<ref name=\"blue\"/> seating 3,300 spectators.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gateshead-fc.com/2487/fa-cup-gateshead-v-brentford-saturday-7th-november-match-information |title=FA Cup: Gateshead v Brentford &nbsp;- Saturday 7th November &nbsp;- Match Information |publisher=[[Gateshead F.C.]] |date=4 November 2009 |accessdate=26 September 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151126120232/http://www.gateshead-fc.com/2487/fa-cup-gateshead-v-brentford-saturday-7th-november-match-information |archivedate=26 November 2015 }}</ref> This stand contains toilet and catering facilities and a bar area.<ref name=\"blue\"/> Opposite is the East Stand, a 4,000-seat structure that was uncovered until 2010, when a cantilevered [[Canopy (building)|canopy]] roof was added. A bespoke design by Fabric Architecture, the roof is a {{convert|30|m|ft}} structure incorporating five [[barrel vault]] forms.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cms.esi.info/Media/documents/80083_1308047032870.pdf|title=Fabric architecture Ltd&nbsp;- Case study: Gateshead International Stadium|publisher=Fabric Architecture|year=2009|accessdate=26 September 2012}}</ref> Part of the same improvement plan added toilet and catering facilities to the East Stand.<ref name=\"covered\"/> The South Terrace, sometimes referred to as simply the South Stand,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/north-east-news/evening-chronicle-news/2012/07/17/queen-to-visit-gateshead-and-newcastle-tomorrow-72703-31410354/ |title=Replay our blog from the Queen's visit to Tyneside |work=[[Evening Chronicle|Newcastle Evening Chronicle]] |date=18 July 2012 |accessdate=9 November 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120822011058/http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/north-east-news/evening-chronicle-news/2012/07/17/queen-to-visit-gateshead-and-newcastle-tomorrow-72703-31410354/ |archivedate=22 August 2012 }}</ref> consists of a continuous, uncovered bank of seating in eight blocks with access through four [[turnstiles]].<ref name=\"UKA Aviva\">{{cite web|url=http://www.uka.org.uk/training-zone/2010/aviva-british-grand-prix/|title=Aviva British Grand Prix|publisher=[[UK Athletics]]|date=10 July 2010|accessdate=9 November 2012}}</ref> The North Terrace is opposite and consists of two blocks of uncovered seating separated by a large scoreboard.<ref name=\"UKA Aviva\"/>\n\n[[File:For athletics.jpg|thumb|left|Hurdles set out on the sprint straight in 2010]]The athletics track in the main arena was laid in 2003 and is an [[International Association of Athletics Federations]] (IAAF) standard 400m eight-lane oval. It is a polymer synthetic [[tartan track]] with a depth of {{convert|3|cm|in|2}}. The sprint straight consists of eight lanes and is situated in front of the Tyne and Wear Stand, adjacent to the [[long jump|long]] and [[triple jump]] area. A height-adjustable water jump, for use in [[Steeplechase (athletics)|steeplechase racing]], is located on the inside of the track.<ref name=\"TrackDir\"/><ref name=\"UKA Aviva\"/><ref name=\"MBCfacts\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gateshead.gov.uk/Leisure%20and%20Culture/sports1/facilities/GIS/home.aspx|title=Gateshead International Stadium|publisher=Gateshead Council|year=2012|accessdate=9 November 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120908102711/https://www.gateshead.gov.uk/Leisure%20and%20Culture/sports1/facilities/GIS/home.aspx|archive-date=8 September 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Floodlights (sport)|Floodlights]] allow athletics events to be held at night.<ref name=\"TrackDir\"/> The inner track area, which is floodlit, is an IAAF standard-sized grass surface used for athletics field events, rugby and football.<ref name=\"MBCfacts\"/> When used for the latter, the pitch dimensions are {{convert|100|x|64|m|yd|1}}.<ref name=\"blue\"/>\n\nThe main arena is supplemented by other facilities. To the rear of the North Terrace are two [[Artificial turf|third generation artificial]] pitches that are [[UEFA]] licensed, fully floodlit and full-sized for use in competitive rugby, football and American football.<ref name=\"pitch up\"/> Alongside them are two grassed and one sand-dressed playing areas, which are also floodlit.<ref name=\"pitch up\"/><ref name=\"MBCfacts\"/> Behind the Tyne and Wear Stand is an indoor sports hall, which contains a {{convert|33|x|44|m|yd|1}} playing area marked out for various sports including badminton, netball and tennis.<ref name=\"MBCfacts\"/> A retractable indoor athletics facility was previously housed alongside the sports hall, consisting of a {{convert|50|m|yd}} long synthetic sprint straight and areas for throwing and jumping events, but its mechanical operation proved problematic<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.runtrackdir.com/details.asp?track=gateshead-s-indoor|title=Gateshead International Stadium Indoor Track|publisher=Running Track Directory|first=Tim|last=Grose|date=30 May 1999|accessdate=9 November 2012}}</ref> and a more modern structure replaced it in 2006. This facility has a {{convert|60|m|yd}} sprint straight in an {{convert|82|m|yd}} hall, throwing and jumping facilities, a weights room and gymnasium.<ref name=\"MBCfacts\"/>\n\n==Athletics==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"float: right; margin-left: 2em; width: 40%; font-size: 90%;\" cellspacing=\"3\"\n|-\n!colspan=\"4\"|World record performances at Gateshead Stadium\n|-\n|'''Athlete name'''||'''Event'''||'''Record mark'''||'''Date'''\n|-\n|{{flagathlete|[[Brendan Foster]]|GBR}}||[[3000 metres|3000m]]||7:35.20||3 August 1974<ref name=\"Gibson 2004:1\"/><ref name=\"UKA\"/>\n|-\n|{{flagathlete|[[Daniela Bartova]]|CZE}}||[[Pole vault]]||4.14m||2 July 1995<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/07/06/sports/track-and-field-american-sprinters-race-past-top-fields.html?pagewanted=2|title=Track and Field; American Sprinters Race Past Top Fields|work=[[The New York Times]]|first=Christopher|last=Clarey|date=6 July 1995|accessdate=22 December 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{flagathlete|[[Yelena Isinbayeva]]|RUS}}||[[Pole vault]]||4.82m||13 July 2003<ref name=\"autogenerated2003\">{{cite web|url=http://www.iaaf.org/news/printer,newsid=21992.htmx|title=Women's World Pole Vault record for Isinbayeva in Gateshead|publisher=[[IAAF]]|date=14 July 2003|accessdate=9 September 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{flagathlete|[[Yelena Isinbayeva]]|RUS}}||[[Pole vault]]||4.87m||27 June 2004<ref name=\"IAAF\">{{cite web|url=http://www.iaaf.org/history/GP/season=2004/news/Kind=2/newsId=25753.html|title=Isinbayeva raises World record to 4.87 in Gateshead|publisher=[[IAAF]]|date=27 June 2004|accessdate=9 September 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{flagathlete|[[Asafa Powell]]|JAM}}||[[100 metres|100m]]||9.77||11 June 2006<ref name=\"rowbottom2006\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/general/athletics-powell-thrills-british-crowd-by-equalling-world-100m-record-482065.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160106153307/http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/general/athletics-powell-thrills-british-crowd-by-equalling-world-100m-record-6098477.html|archivedate=6 January 2016|title=Athletics: Powell thrills British crowd by equalling world 100m record|first=Mike|last=Rowbottom|work=[[The Independent]]|date=12 June 2006|accessdate=9 September 2012}}</ref>\n|}\n\nThe first major athletic event held at the stadium was the Vaux Breweries International Athletics meet in July 1961. According to its sponsors, the highlight of this meet was the team three-mile race, won by the Blackpool and Fylde Athletic club who were awarded a gold tankard as their prize.<ref name=\"BGR\"/> Attracted by a prize fund of \u00a3500 and the imminent [[AAA Championships]] in London, the event attracted several athletes from New Zealand, including [[Athletics at the 1960 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 5000 metres|reigning 5000m metre Olympic champion]] [[Murray Halberg]] and [[Peter Snell]], the [[Athletics at the 1960 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 800 metres|reigning 800m Olympic champion]].<ref name=\"McGuirk\"/> Watched by a capacity crowd of 10,000 spectators, the men won their respective races; Halberg placed first in the [[Mile run|mile]] with a time of 4:03:70 and Snell led a [[New Zealand]] one-two in the 880-yard event, finishing ahead of teammate Gary Philpott in 1:50:40.<ref name=\"McGuirk\"/>\n\nWhen the comprehensive refurbishment of the stadium was completed more than a decade later, Brendan Foster (by this time a Gateshead Council employee) proposed an international athletics meet. On 3&nbsp;August 1974, the first \"Gateshead Games\" were staged in front of around 10,000 spectators.<ref name=\"Gibson 2004:1\"/><ref name=\"UKA\"/> Four weeks before he won the European 5000m title at the [[1974 European Athletics Championships]] in Rome, Foster kept his earlier promise to run in the men's 3000m and won the race in a new world-record time of 7:35:20. According to journalist John Gibson, Foster's performance gave the meet, broadcast live by [[Tyne Tees Television]], \"landmark status\".<ref name=\"Gibson 2004:1\"/><ref name=\"UKA\"/> A plaque commemorating the record was later placed at the entrance to the stadium.<ref name=\"ICN\"/>\n\nThe Gateshead Games became an annual event, which gave the stadium credibility as a major sporting venue.<ref name=\"ICN\"/><ref name=\"Gibson 2004:1\"/> In his managerial capacity with Gateshead Council, Foster was increasingly able to attract athletes to the games. In 1977, Foster had to intervene when [[BBC Radio Newcastle]] provided the wrong [[Ethiopian national anthem]] which, when played, offended [[Miruts Yifter]] sufficiently that he and his teammates started off towards [[Newcastle International Airport]]. The intervention worked\u2014in the end, Foster asked Yifter and his teammates if they would sing the anthem themselves, which they did in the middle of the stadium\u2014and Yifter returned to outclass a field including [[Steve Ovett]] over 5000m.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://icnewcastle.icnetwork.co.uk/0200sport/0600athletics/tm_objectid=14208798%26method=full%26siteid=50081%26headline=face-to-face--brendan-foster-name_page.html |title=Face to Face: Brendan Foster |first=John |last=Gibson |work=[[Newcastle Evening Chronicle]] |date=4 May 2004 |accessdate=28 December 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151230110849/http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/sport/other-sport/face-to-face-brendan-foster-1615997 |archivedate=30 December 2015 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref> The track was resurfaced by Regisport in 1982<ref name=\"TrackDir\">{{cite web|url=http://www.runtrackdir.com/details.asp?track=gateshead&country=uk|title=Gateshead International Stadium|publisher=Running Track Directory|date=25 March 2010|accessdate=30 August 2012}} This site is a redirect from the UK Athletics website.</ref> and the venues' profile was further raised in the summer of 1983, when Gateshead-born athlete [[Steve Cram]]{{refn|group=nb|UK Athletics state that Cram was born in Gateshead,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uka.org.uk/e-inspire/hall-of-fame-athletes/steve-cram/|title=Hall of Fame Athletes &ndash; Steve Cram|publisher=[[UK Athletics]]|year=2012|accessdate=11 November 2012}}</ref> as does an interview with Cram by ''Track and Field News'' in September 1985.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.trackandfieldnews.com/archive/Interviews/Steve%20Cram.pdf |title=T & F N &ndash; Interview, Steve Cram |work=Track and Field News |first=Steve |last=Powell |date=12 September 1985 |accessdate=12 November 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130524060213/http://www.trackandfieldnews.com/archive/Interviews/Steve%20Cram.pdf |archivedate=24 May 2013 }}</ref> Other sources, including an article from the [[University of Sunderland]] website, claim he was born in [[Jarrow]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://services.sunderland.ac.uk/universitysport/newsevents/news/news/index.php?nid=500|title=News Story &ndash; Steve Cram named new Chancellor|publisher=[[University of Sunderland]]|date=23 May 2008|accessdate=12 November 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120321190504/http://services.sunderland.ac.uk/universitysport/newsevents/news/news/index.php?nid=500|archivedate=21 March 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>}} faced Sebastian Coe over 800m in the Gateshead Games. In front of a reported crowd of 15,000 who were \"shoehorned into the bowl\" and millions more watching on BBC's [[Sunday Grandstand]], Cram prevailed to spark \"pandemonium\" in his final race before winning the gold medal at the [[1983 World Championships in Athletics|1983 World Athletics Championships]] in Helsinki.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/sport/other-sport/face-to-face-steve-cram-1533194 |title=Face to Face: Steve Cram |first=John |last=Gibson |work=[[Newcastle Evening Chronicle]] |date=2 May 2006 |accessdate=2 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 1989, Gateshead hosted the [[1989 European Cup (athletics)|Europa Cup]]. The men's competition was won for the first time by a Great Britain team captained by [[Linford Christie]] and which included [[Kriss Akabusi]] and [[Jack Buckner]]; the event was described a decade later as having had an \"invigorating effect\" on those who were in attendance.<ref name=\"Europa1\"/> Four years later, on 30 July 1993, a stadium-record crowd of 14,797<ref name=\"McGuirk\"/> watched Christie, by this time [[Athletics at the 1992 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 100 metres|the reigning 100m Olympic champion]], in action again &ndash; this time against his old rival [[Carl Lewis]] in a race where both men were reportedly paid \u00a3100,000 irrespective of the result.<ref name=\"Rowbottom\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/athletics-climate-and-form-point-to-a-christie-victory-world-and-olympic-champions-play-down-the-implications-of-tonights-gateshead-showdown-for-world-championships-in-stuttgart-1488119.html|title=Athletics: Climate and form point to a Christie victory: World and Olympic champions play down the implications of tonight's Gateshead showdown for World Championships in Stuttgart|first=Mike|last=Rowbottom|work=[[The Independent]]|date=30 July 1993|accessdate=9 September 2012}}</ref> Christie won in a time of 10.07 seconds, ahead of [[Jon Drummond]] in second and Lewis, who finished \"a distant third\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/general/athletics/jamaican-sprinters-yohan-blake-and-usain-bolt-refuse-to-race-headtohead-8092692.html|title=Jamaican sprinters Yohan Blake and Usain Bolt refuse to race head-to-head |first=Simon|last=Turnbull|work=[[The Independent]]|date=30 August 2012|accessdate=9 September 2012}}</ref> The 100m race was the highlight of the \"high profile\" Vauxhall Invitational meet, which was televised in the UK by [[ITV (TV channel)|ITV]] and watched by around 10 million viewers. [[Michael Johnson (sprinter)|Michael Johnson]], [[John Regis (athlete)|John Regis]] and Steve Cram competed in various events at the Vauxhall Invitational.<ref name=\"Rowbottom\"/>\n\nIn August 1998, Gateshead was selected to host the [[2000 European Cup (athletics)|2000 Europa Cup]] after the [[European Athletic Association]] switched the event from original host venue [[Martinique]] to avoid athletes travelling long distances in an Olympic year.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/athletics-gatesheads-european-cup-1173824.html|title=Athletics: Gateshead's European Cup|work=[[The Independent]]|date=24 August 1998|accessdate=9 September 2012}}</ref> This made Gateshead the first venue to host the event twice.<ref name=\"Diamond\">{{cite web|url=http://www.diamondleague.com/News/News-Archive/An-athletics-snapshot-of-GATESHEAD/|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130121222720/http://www.diamondleague.com/News/News-Archive/An-athletics-snapshot-of-GATESHEAD/|url-status=dead|archive-date=21 January 2013|title=An athletic snapshot of Gateshead|first=David|last=Powell|publisher=Diamond League.com|date=20 November 2009|accessdate=9 September 2012}}</ref> On 16&ndash;17 July 2000, spectators at Gateshead once again saw Great Britain's men's team take the title, this time by half a point from Germany in second place; the British victory came despite missing ten first-choice team members. The women's event was won by Russia, who defeated second-placed Germany by thirteen points.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/athletics/4759741/European-Cup-Athletics-Relay-squad-find-Britains-winning-kick.html|title=European Cup Athletics: Relay squad find Britain's winning kick|first=Brendan|last=Gallagher|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=17 July 2000|accessdate=9 September 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Paula Radcliffe 2005.jpg|right|upright|border|thumb|[[Paula Radcliffe]] runs the 10,000m at Gateshead in 2004]]Foster's \"Gateshead Games\" had become the [[British Grand Prix (athletics)|British Grand Prix]] by 2003, and on 13 July 21-year-old [[Yelena Isinbayeva]] set a [[Women's pole vault world record progression|new world record]] of 4.82m in the women's [[pole vault]] event. Isinbayeva's achievement in the last event of the meet was so unexpected that only 1,000 of the 10,000 spectators witnessed it, the rest having left early. For her achievement, she was given a bonus cheque for $50,000.<ref name=\"autogenerated2003\"/> On 27 June 2004, Isinbayeva returned to Gateshead. This time the event organisers decided to schedule the pole vault event earlier and were rewarded when Isinbayeva defied extremely windy conditions to post a new record mark of 4.87m.<ref name=\"IAAF\"/> Isinbayeva was the second woman to set a world record in the pole vault at Gateshead; [[Daniela Bartova]] did so in 1995.<ref name=\"Diamond\"/> In 2006, a crowd of 8,500 saw [[Asafa Powell]] equal the world record of 9.77 seconds in the [[100 metres|men's 100m]]. The official, un-rounded time of 9.762 seconds was then the fastest time ever recorded. The meet was also notable for the return to competition of [[Dwain Chambers]] after his ban for using [[Tetrahydrogestrinone|performance-enhancing drugs]], and for [[Eliud Kipchoge]] breaking Foster's stadium record over 3000m that had stood for more than three decades.<ref name=\"rowbottom2006\"/>\n\nIn 2010, the British Grand Prix at Gateshead was chosen as one of the inaugural fourteen [[IAAF Diamond League 2010|Diamond League]] events,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uka.org.uk/media/news/news-archive-pre-2011/april-2010/30-04-10-gay/|title=Diamond League|publisher=[[UK Athletics]]|date=30 April 2010|accessdate=9 September 2012}}</ref> but although competitors included [[Tyson Gay]], Powell, [[Jessica Ennis]] and [[Vincent Chepkok]], the attendance was unusually poor, causing the local press to wonder whether Gateshead's contract for the marquee event would be renewed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.journallive.co.uk/newcastle-sports/newcastle-sports/athletics-news/2010/07/12/tyson-gay-beats-asafa-powell-at-gateshead-stadium-61634-26831826/|title=Tyson Gay beats Asafa Powell at Gateshead Stadium|first=Stuart|last=Rayner|work=[[The Journal (newspaper)|The Journal]]|date=12 July 2010|accessdate=9 September 2012}}</ref> Those fears were to prove well-founded when [[UK Athletics]] agreed to a three-year contract to stage the event at the [[Alexander Stadium]] in Birmingham.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uka.org.uk/media/news/news-archive-pre-2011/november-2010/22-11-10-aviva-birmingham-grand-prix/|title=aviva birmingham grand prix|publisher=[[UK Athletics]]|date=22 November 2010|accessdate=9 September 2012}}</ref> The move prompted one reporter to lament that \"the switch is a major blow to both Gateshead International Stadium and North-East sport in general, but can hardly be regarded as a major surprise given the dwindling support for major athletics events in the region.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/sport/8679464.North_East_athletics_loses_its_flagship_event/|title=North-East athletics loses its flagship event|first=Scott|last=Wilson|work=[[The Northern Echo]]|date=21 November 2010|accessdate=9 September 2012}}</ref>\n\nThis loss was mitigated somewhat by the European Athletic Association's decision to award Gateshead the [[2013 European Team Championships]], the successor to the Europa Cup.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.european-athletics.org/competitions/european-team-championships/news/article=gateshead-host-2013-European-athletics-team-championships/index.html |title=Gateshead to host 2013 European Athletics Team Championships |publisher=[[European Athletics Association]] |date=June 2011 |accessdate=2 October 2016}}</ref> In doing so, Gateshead became the only stadium to host the European Team Championships on three occasions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.athleticsweekly.com/news/gateshead-awarded-2013-european-team-championships/ |title=Gateshead awarded 2013 European Team Championships |work=[[Athletics Weekly]] |date=6 June 2011 |accessdate=9 September 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110816005537/http://www.athleticsweekly.com/news/gateshead-awarded-2013-european-team-championships/ |archivedate=16 August 2011 }}</ref> The championships were held on 22&ndash;23 June 2013 amid very wet and windy conditions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/athletics/23023977|title=European team Championships: GB secure third place|publisher=[[BBC|the BBC]]|date=23 June 2015|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref> On the first day of competition, [[Mo Farah]] ran a 50.89 second final lap in winning the men's 5000m to help the home team into third place on 181 points, behind Russia (194 points) and Germany (195 points).<ref>{{cite book|title=Souped-up Mo Farah turns into Billy Whizz at the European Team Championships|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/general/athletics/souped-up-mo-farah-turns-into-billy-whizz-at-the-european-team-championships-8669844.html|work=[[The Independent]]|first=Simon|last=Turnbull|date=22 June 2013|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref> Despite a strong start, the Great Britain team were unable to make up the deficit on the second day of competition and finished in third place overall on 338 points, behind runners-up Germany (347.5 points) and the champions Russia (354.5 points).<ref>{{cite book|title=GB youngsters delight Peter Eriksson at European Team Championships |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2013/jun/23/gb-peter-eriksson-european-team-championships|work=[[The Guardian]]|first=Sean|last=Ingle|date=23 June 2013|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nDue to redevelopment of Birmingham\u2019s Alexander Stadium for the [[2022 Commonwealth Games|2022 commonwealth games]], the [[British Grand Prix (athletics)|British Grand Prix]] Diamond League fixture is set to return to Gateshead in 2020 for the first time in 10 years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.athleticsweekly.com/athletics-news/gateshead-included-in-2020-diamond-league-season-1039926187/|title=Gateshead included in 2020 Diamond League season|last=|first=|date=October 22, 2019|website=Athletics Weekly|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 30, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Tenants==\n\n===Gateshead Football Club===\n{{main|Gateshead F.C.}}\nThe stadium was briefly used by former Football League members [[Gateshead A.F.C.]] after leaving [[Redheugh Park]] in 1971, but the club went bust in 1973.<ref name=UD>Paul Smith & Shirley Smith (2005) ''The Ultimate Directory of English & Scottish Football League Grounds Second Edition 1888\u20132005'', Yore Publications, p70, {{ISBN|0954783042}}</ref> The following year South Shields football club relocated to Gateshead and were renamed [[Gateshead United F.C.|Gateshead United]]; they played at the Gateshead Stadium from 1974 to 1977 when they folded and [[Gateshead F.C.]] was formed.<ref name=\"GFC history\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gateshead-fc.com/club-history|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130206113453/http://www.gateshead-fc.com/club-history|url-status=dead|archive-date=6 February 2013|title=The History of Gateshead Football Club|first=Jeff|last=Bowron|publisher=[[Gateshead F.C.]]|year=2012|accessdate=15 September 2012}}</ref>\n\nGateshead F.C. have been tenants since their formation in 1977.<ref name=\"GFC history\"/> In May 2008 Gateshead hosted [[Buxton F.C.|Buxton]] in a promotion play-off and won 2&ndash;0 in front of 1,402 spectators, the largest crowd to watch the club at the ground in 14 years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Bogie%27s+over+the+Toon+with+victory%3B+Gateshead+clinch+promotion+with...-a0178633259|title=Bogie's over the Toon with victory|first=Jeff|last=Bowron|work=[[Evening Chronicle|Newcastle Evening Chronicle]]|date=5 May 2008|accessdate=22 December 2012}}</ref> That record was broken a year later when 4,121 saw Gateshead defeat [[A.F.C. Telford United|Telford United]] 2&ndash;0 on 9&nbsp;May 2009 to win promotion to the [[Conference Premier]] league.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gateshead-fc.com/2282/gateshead-1-0-afc-telford-united |title=Gateshead 1&ndash;0 AFC Telford United |first=Jeff |last=Bowron |publisher=[[Gateshead F.C.]] |date=10 May 2009 |accessdate=15 September 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120830031215/http://www.gateshead-fc.com/2282/gateshead-1-0-afc-telford-united |archivedate=30 August 2012 }}</ref> The current record attendance for a competitive fixture stands at 8,144, set on 4&nbsp;May 2014 when Gateshead played host to [[Grimsby Town F.C.|Grimsby Town]] in the second leg of the [[2013-14 Football Conference#Play-offs|Conference Premier play-off]] semi-final.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/27193080|title=Gateshead 3&ndash;1 Grimsby Town|first=Joe|last=Townsend|publisher=[[BBC|the BBC]]|date=4 May 2014|accessdate=21 May 2014}}</ref> Gateshead won 3-1 to progress to the final at [[Wembley Stadium]] where they were beaten 2-1 by [[Cambridge United F.C.|Cambridge United]]. The defeat consigned the club to a 55th consecutive season outside the Football League.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/27360422|title=Cambridge 2&ndash;1 Gateshead|first=Chris|last=Osborne|publisher=[[BBC|the BBC]]|date=18 May 2014|accessdate=21 May 2014}}</ref> Gateshead F.C. continue to play at Gateshead Stadium but, according to North East Life magazine, it is \"a fine but inappropriate stadium&nbsp;... as a football ground it can be a soulless home\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://northeast.greatbritishlife.co.uk/article/gateshead-fc-dare-to-dream-37130/ |title=Gateshead FC dare to dream |publisher=North East Life |year=2012 |accessdate=15 September 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140515155612/http://www.northeastlifemag.co.uk/out-about/gateshead_fc_dare_to_dream_1_1648041 |archivedate=15 May 2014 |url-status=dead}}</ref> In 2009, chairman Graham Wood unveiled plans to move to a new, purpose-built 9,000 capacity ground on Prince Consort Road in the centre of Gateshead.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/tyne/8330448.stm|title=Football stadium plans unveiled|publisher=[[BBC|the BBC]]|date=28 October 2009|accessdate=15 September 2012}}</ref> Detailed proposals were published soon after,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gateshead-fc.com/new-stadium |title=Gateshead's New Stadium |publisher=[[Gateshead F.C.]] |year=2009 |accessdate=15 September 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120831210336/http://www.gateshead-fc.com/new-stadium |archivedate=31 August 2012 }}</ref> and Wood told local media in 2012 that he expects the move to increase crowds and alleviate the financial constraints on him as he continues to bankroll the club; it is estimated that crowds would need to reach 3,000 regularly for the club to operate profitably from Gateshead Stadium.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/sport/football/non-league-football/2012/08/23/grounds-for-hope-over-new-gateshead-fc-stadium-72703-31679339/|title=Grounds for hope over new Gateshead FC stadium|work=[[Evening Chronicle|Newcastle Evening Chronicle]]|first=Steve|last=Brown|date=23 August 2012|accessdate=28 December 2012}}</ref> According to the original proposal, the stadium was expected to be ready for the 2012&ndash;13 season, but financing has been difficult and the proposed move is now on hold.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/sport/football/non-league-football/2011/06/06/optimism-over-gateshead-s-new-stadium-plans-72703-28827957/ |title=Optimism over Gateshead's new stadium plans |work=[[Evening Chronicle|Newcastle Evening Chronicle]] |date=6 June 2011 |accessdate=28 December 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110625011823/http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/sport/football/non-league-football/2011/06/06/optimism-over-gateshead-s-new-stadium-plans-72703-28827957/ |archivedate=25 June 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.journallive.co.uk/north-east-news/todays-news/2012/10/09/athletes-forced-to-make-way-for-footballers-at-gateshead-stadium-61634-31994732/|title=Athletes forced to make way for footballers at Gateshead Stadium|work=[[The Journal (newspaper)|The Journal]]|first=Michael|last=Brown|date=9 October 2012|accessdate=28 December 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Gateshead Harriers===\n\n[[Gateshead Harriers]] are an athletic club based at Gateshead International Stadium. Founded in 1904 as Gateshead St Mary's Church Running Club, they were initially a men-only club until allowing the admission of women in 1951. The club moved to the Gateshead Youth Stadium in 1956, making the Harriers the stadium's oldest tenant.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gateshead-harriers.co.uk/home/ |title=Welcome to Gateshead Harriers |publisher=Gateshead Harriers |year=2012 |accessdate=16 September 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120628164804/http://www.gateshead-harriers.co.uk/home/ |archivedate=28 June 2012 }}</ref> In 2006 they won promotion to the first division of the [[British Athletics League]] and were the only club from the north-east of England to compete at that level.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/sport/other-sport/harriers-join-big-league-1533578|title=Harriers join big league|first=Bill|last=McGuirk|work=[[Evening Chronicle|Newcastle Evening Chronicle]]|date=4 May 2006|accessdate=2 October 2016}}</ref> After a six-year stay in the division, the Harriers were relegated to division two in August 2012 after failing to win enough points at the final meet of the season at Eton to prevent a bottom-two league finish.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/sport/athletics-news/2012/08/20/battling-gateshead-harriers-fail-to-beat-relegation-72703-31656928/|title=Battling Gateshead Harriers fail to beat relegation|work=[[Evening Chronicle|Newcastle Evening Chronicle]]|date=22 August 2012|accessdate=16 September 2012}}</ref> Club officials received over 100 new applications for membership in the aftermath of [[2012 Olympics|the 2012 London Olympics]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/sport/athletics-news/2012/08/30/london-2012-olympics-legacy-is-up-and-running-72703-31725773/|title=London 2012 Olympics legacy is up and running|first=Bill|last=McGuirk|work=[[Evening Chronicle|Newcastle Evening Chronicle]]|date=30 August 2012|accessdate=16 September 2012}}</ref>\n\nAt least one Gateshead Harrier has taken part in every Olympics and [[Paralympic Games|Paralympics]] held since 1972.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gateshead.gov.uk/People%20and%20Living/award/award.aspx|title=The Gateshead Award|publisher=Gateshead Council|year=2012|accessdate=16 September 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120916144454/http://www.gateshead.gov.uk/People%20and%20Living/award/award.aspx|archive-date=16 September 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Notable alumni include Brendan Foster, who joined the club aged 17 and later claimed that \"my first aim was to be the best runner of Gateshead Harriers\".<ref>Luhtala, 2002: 94</ref> Foster, inducted into the [[England Athletics Hall of Fame]] in 2010 and recently voted the eleventh \"greatest [[Geordie]]\" in a local poll, later became the president of Gateshead Harriers and remains so as of 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/sport/athletics-news/2010/11/04/brendan-foster-inducted-into-hall-of-fame-72703-27599438/ |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120729152531/http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/sport/athletics-news/2010/11/04/brendan-foster-inducted-into-hall-of-fame-72703-27599438/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=29 July 2012 |title=Brendan Foster inducted into Hall of Fame |first=Bill |last=McGuirk |work=[[Evening Chronicle|Newcastle Evening Chronicle]] |date=4 November 2010 |accessdate=16 September 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/north-east-news/evening-chronicle-news/2012/08/28/chronicle-s-100-greatest-geordies-no-s-12-to-10-72703-31711383/2/ |title=Chronicle's 100 Greatest Geordies, Nos 10&ndash;12 |first=Michael |last=Kelly |work=[[Evening Chronicle|Newcastle Evening Chronicle]] |date=28 August 2012 |accessdate=16 September 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120831210752/http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/north-east-news/evening-chronicle-news/2012/08/28/chronicle-s-100-greatest-geordies-no-s-12-to-10-72703-31711383/2/ |archivedate=31 August 2012 }}</ref> Current world triple-jump record holder [[Jonathan Edwards (triple jumper)|Jonathan Edwards]], another member of the England Athletics Hall of Fame,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.englandathletics.org/page.asp?section=847&sectionTitle=Hall+of+Fame+2009+inductees|title=Hall of Fame &ndash; Inductees 2009|publisher=[[England Athletics Hall of Fame]]|year=2009|accessdate=16 September 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120514041704/http://englandathletics.org/page.asp?section=847&sectionTitle=Hall+of+Fame+2009+inductees|archive-date=14 May 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> joined Gateshead Harriers in 1991. Edwards was a member of the club when he set his record mark in [[1995 World Championships in Athletics \u2013 Men's triple jump|winning gold]] at the [[1995 World Championships in Athletics|1995 World Championships]] in Helsinki, when winning [[Athletics at the 2000 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's triple jump|Olympic gold]] at the [[2000 Summer Olympics|2000 Sydney Games]] and a [[2001 World Championships in Athletics \u2013 Men's triple jump|second world title]] a year later in [[Edmonton]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/1477695.stm|title=North east toasts hero Edwards|publisher=[[BBC|the BBC]]|date=7 August 2001|accessdate=16 September 2012}}</ref> Both Foster and Edwards are honorary life members of the club.<ref>Miller, 2008: 173</ref>\n\n===Gateshead Thunder===\n{{main|Newcastle Thunder}}\n[[File:Gateshead vs limoux.jpg|thumb|upright|right|[[Newcastle Thunder|Gateshead Thunder]] playing against Limoux in the [[Challenge Cup]] at Gateshead International Stadium in 2004]]In 1998, Gateshead was awarded a [[rugby league]] franchise after a three-way contest with Cardiff and Swansea. The result was Gateshead Thunder, who played in [[Super League IV]] in 1999.<ref name=\"OFT\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thunderrugby.com/page.php?id=940|title=Club History &ndash; Super League|publisher=Gateshead Thunder|year=2012|accessdate=16 September 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120822071422/http://www.thunderrugby.com/page.php?id=940|archivedate=22 August 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The Thunder played at Gateshead International Stadium and the club had, according to sports journalist Andy Wilson, \"an enjoyable and surprisingly successful season\" which included home and away wins against [[St Helens R.F.C.|St. Helens]] and a sixth-place finish in the table &ndash; missing out on the playoffs by two points.<ref name=\"Guard\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2009/may/29/rugby-league-challenge-cup-gateshead|title=Gateshead Thunder are ready to make a big noise against St Helens|first=Andy|last=Wilson|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=29 May 2009|accessdate=16 September 2012}}</ref> Despite these performances, which attracted an average crowd of 3,895 to Gateshead Stadium, the franchise lost \u00a3700,000 in its first year<ref name=\"OFT\"/> and in November 1999 the [[Rugby Football League]] (RFL) approved a merger with the Hull Sharks.<ref name=\"bbcrfl\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sport/rugby_league/521562.stm|title=Rugby League League's northern empire cut back|publisher=[[BBC|the BBC]]|date=19 November 2012|accessdate=16 September 2012}}</ref> The result was the formation of [[Hull F.C.|Hull FC]], and when the authorities refused permission for the merged clubs to enter a Hull-based team into the RFL's [[Rugby Football League Championship Second Division|second tier]],<ref name=\"OFT\"/> the franchise moved almost in its entirety to Hull, ending Gateshead's Super League participation after a single season; according to Wilson, the Thunder was \"left to die, provoking bitter resentment\" from supporters.<ref name=\"Guard\"/>\n\nAccording to journalist Richard Bott, since the demise of the original Thunder side the club has \"struggled for their very existence.\"<ref name=\"mail\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/rugbyleague/article-1189626/Thorman-keeps-family-Gateshead-skipper-looks-forward-giant-Cup-clash.html|title=Thorman keeps it in the family as Gateshead skipper looks forward to giant Cup clash|first=Richard|last=Bott|work=[[Daily Mail]]|date=29 May 2009|accessdate=16 September 2012}}</ref> There have been some highlights, including winning [[RFL League 1|Championship 1]] in 2008<ref name=\"OFT\"/> and a run to the quarter-final of the [[Challenge Cup]] in 2009 which ended in a 66&ndash;6 defeat to Super League side St Helens in front of 4,325 fans at Gateshead International Stadium.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/rugbyleague/article-1189815/Gateshead-6-St-Helens-66-Saints-march-fourth-Wembley.html|title=Gateshead 6 St Helens 66: Saints march fourth towards Wembley|work=[[Daily Mail]]|date=30 May 2009|accessdate=16 September 2012}}</ref> However, the Thunder went through a 64-game losing streak spanning two-and-a-half years before winning against [[Workington Town]] on 29 August 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/sport/rugby-news/gateshead-thunder/2012/08/30/gateshead-thunder-in-shock-victory-over-visitors-72703-31725698/ |title=Gateshead Thunder in shock victory over visitors |work=[[Evening Chronicle|Newcastle Evening Chronicle]] |date=30 August 2012 |accessdate=16 September 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130119021745/http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/sport/rugby-news/gateshead-thunder/2012/08/30/gateshead-thunder-in-shock-victory-over-visitors-72703-31725698/ |archivedate=19 January 2013 }}</ref>\n\nRelations between the Thunder and Gateshead Council were strained at times, with a possible move to [[Kingston Park (stadium)|Kingston Park]] [[Newcastle upon Tyne]], first mooted, and rejected, in 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sundaysun.co.uk/sport/rugby-north-east/2006/05/10/sights-set-on-top-flight-79310-17055903/|title=Sights set on top flight|first=Jeff|last=Bowron|work=[[Sunday Sun|The Sunday Sun]]|date=10 May 2006|accessdate=16 September 2012}}</ref> In 2008, the club committed itself again to Gateshead Stadium for the immediate future,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/2008/10/30/thunder-agree-deal-to-continue-playing-at-stadium-72703-22150967/|title=Thunder agree deal to continue playing at Stadium|first=Nick|last=Purewal|work=[[Evening Chronicle|Newcastle Evening Chronicle]]|date=30 October 2008|accessdate=16 September 2012}}</ref> however, in March 2014 [[The Journal (newspaper)|The Journal]] reported that talks had begun between Thunder's managing director Keith Christie and representatives of [[Newcastle Falcons]] with a view to the Falcons taking over the rugby league club.<ref>{{cite book|title=Newcastle Falcons set to take over Newcastle Thunder|url=http://www.thejournal.co.uk/sport/rugby-union/newcastle-falcons-set-take-over-6772996|work=[[The Journal (newspaper)|The Journal]]|first=Mark|last=Smith|date=5 March 2014|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref> Falcons' owner Semore Kurdi confirmed that a bid had been made to purchase Gateshead Thunder on 20 March 2014, though he refused to elaborate on whether he intended to relocate the club if that bid was accepted.<ref>{{cite book|title=Newcastle Falcons confirm bid to buy Gateshead Thunder|url=http://www.thejournal.co.uk/sport/rugby-union/newcastle-falcons-confirm-bid-buy-6854075|work=[[The Journal (newspaper)|The Journal]]|first=Mark|last=Smith|date=20 March 2014|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref> The takeover was confirmed on 23 May 2014, though it was announced that the club would continue to play at the International Stadium.<ref>{{cite book|title=Newcastle Falcons unite rugby codes in Gateshead Thunder takeover|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/sport/other-sport/rugby-league/newcastle-falcons-unite-rugby-codes-7162734|work=[[Evening Chronicle]]|first=Mark|last=Smith|date=23 May 2014|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref> In January 2015 Gateshead Thunder were officially renamed Newcastle Thunder and relocated to Kingston Park. Keith Christie told the BBC that the move was \"a business decision\" designed to build a new fan base for the club.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-league/30901286|title=Newcastle Thunder: Gateshead rugby league side relocates|publisher=[[BBC|The BBC]]|date=20 January 2015|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Gateshead Senators===\n{{main|Gateshead Senators}}\nThe [[Gateshead Senators]] (originally the Gateshead International Senators) are an [[American football]] club formed in 1988 when the Newcastle Senators, who played at Northern Rugby Club, moved across the Tyne to play at the Gateshead International Stadium.<ref name=\"SenHistory\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gateshead-senators.com/history.html|title=Gateshead Senators &ndash; History|publisher=Gateshead&ndash;Senators.com|year=2012|accessdate=15 September 2012}}</ref> The club has had mixed fortunes but their most successful season came in 1999. Having won eight of their nine games in the regular season, the team won the Division One North title and advanced to the end-of-season playoffs. After beating the Merseyside Nighthawks 43&ndash;0 in the quarter-finals, the Senators defeated the [[Essex Spartans]] 33&ndash;19 in the semi-finals to reach the championship final. At the [[Saffron Lane sports centre|Saffron Lane Stadium]] in [[Leicester]], the Senators faced the [[Bristol Aztecs (American football)|Bristol Aztecs]]. In a tight encounter, the Senators claimed the Division One [[British American Football League]] title with a 7&ndash;2 victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.users.zetnet.co.uk/pcrrn/senators/final99.htm|title=Gateshead Senators Division One Champions|publisher=[[Gateshead Senators]]|year=1999|accessdate=17 November 2012}} This site is a redirect from the official history links provided on the Gateshead Senators website.</ref> The club reached the playoffs again in the next three seasons but were unable to replicate that success, and after a season voluntarily spent in Division Two in 2003, returned to Division One North in 2004. They continue to play in that division, and in the 2012 season failed to make the playoffs after recording five wins and five defeats in their ten games.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bafanl.co.uk/team/18 |title=Gateshead Senators |publisher=[[BAFA National Leagues|British American Football National League]] |year=2012 |accessdate=17 November 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130126004959/http://www.bafanl.co.uk/team/18 |archivedate=26 January 2013 }}</ref>\n\nThe Senators were a tenant at Gateshead Stadium from 1988 to 2011.<ref name=\"SenHistory\"/> In 2012, the club announced plans to move away from Gateshead for the start of the 2012 season to create \"a better game-day experience\" and they now play at the [[Monkton Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Grounds+for+optimism+over+Senators%27+switch%3B+AMERICAN+FOOTBALL.-a0277972301|title=Grounds for optimism over Senators switch|work=[[Evening Chronicle|Newcastle Evening Chronicle]]|date=25 January 2012|accessdate=22 December 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Concert venue==\n\nGateshead International Stadium has been used for many years as a concert venue.<ref>{{cite news|title=Gebrselassie set to star at Gateshead|first=Alan|last=Pattullo|work=[[The Scotsman]]|date=2 June 1999}}</ref> On 31 July 1982, [[The Police]] performed at the stadium as part of their [[Ghost in the Machine Tour]], with [[U2]] as a supporting act. Reports in the local press suggested that The Police seemed disappointed that the stadium was only half full and cited high ticket prices and poor weather as possible causes.<ref>{{cite news|title=Lukewarm greeting as hero returns|first=Bill|last=Brown|work=[[The Journal (newspaper)|The Journal]]|date=1 August 1982}}</ref> On 16 June 1992 [[Guns N' Roses]], supported by [[Soundgarden]] and [[Faith No More]], performed at the stadium. This time the weather was hot and sunny which helped ensure that the concert, part of the [[Use Your Illusion Tour]], was a sell-out.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/2012/05/11/interview-dizzy-reed-ahead-of-guns-n-roses-gig-72703-30948744/ |title=Interview: Dizzy Reed ahead of Guns N' Roses gig |first=Mick |last=Burgess |work=[[Evening Chronicle|Newcastle Evening Chronicle]] |date=11 May 2012 |accessdate=9 November 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120513135831/http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/2012/05/11/interview-dizzy-reed-ahead-of-guns-n-roses-gig-72703-30948744/ |archivedate=13 May 2012 }}</ref> American rock group [[Bon Jovi]] have played twice at the stadium. The first occasion was on 27 June 1995, while supported by [[Skin (British band)|Skin]], on their [[These Days Tour]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/multimedia/entertainment/2012/10/30/flashback-bon-jovi-play-the-gateshead-stadium-72703-32129039/#2 |title=Flashback: Bon Jovi play the Gateshead Stadium |work=[[Evening Chronicle|Newcastle Evening Chronicle]] |date=30 October 2012 |accessdate=9 November 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130201182841/http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/multimedia/entertainment/2012/10/30/flashback-bon-jovi-play-the-gateshead-stadium-72703-32129039/ |archivedate=1 February 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skinfreak.co.uk/biography|title=Biography|publisher=Skin: The Official Website|year=2012|accessdate=9 November 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105225131/http://www.skinfreak.co.uk/biography|archive-date=5 November 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The group returned to Gateshead on 22 August 2000 as part of their [[Crush Tour]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/893047.stm|title=Bon Jovi delights British fans|publisher=[[BBC|the BBC]]|date=23 August 2000|accessdate=9 November 2012}}</ref> Another artist who has performed multiple times at Gateshead International Stadium is [[Tina Turner]]. As part of her [[Foreign Affair: The Farewell Tour]], Turner performed twice on consecutive nights (21&ndash;22 July 1990) and attracted a total of 60,000 spectators.<ref>Welch, 1995: 192</ref> Turner performed for a third time at the stadium as part of her [[Wildest Dreams Tour]] on 12 July 1996.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/TINA.-a061156467|title=Tina|first=Lisa|last=Burrows|work=[[The People]]|date=26 May 1996|accessdate=22 December 2012}}</ref> Most recently the venue played host to [[Little Mix]] on 26 July 2018 as part of their [[Summer Hits Tour 2018|Summer Hits Tour]]. Other artists to have played at the stadium include [[Bryan Adams]], [[Rod Stewart]], [[Simple Minds]] and [[Simply Red]].<ref>{{cite news|title=A billion fans bowl star over |first=Sonia |last=Sharma |work=[[Evening Chronicle|Newcastle Evening Chronicle]] |date=27 January 2003 |page=12}}</ref>\n\n==Transport==\n\n[[File:Gateshead Stadium Metro Station - geograph.org.uk - 70792.jpg|thumb|[[Gateshead Stadium Metro station]]]]\nGateshead International Stadium is {{convert|2|mi|km|0}} east of Gateshead Town Centre and is on the [[A184 road (England)#Triple-digit roads|A184 Felling Bypass]], with access to a car park at Neilson Road.<ref>Report to Cabinet &ndash; Gateshead International Stadium &ndash; Draft Development Brief, 2010: 7 at para.15</ref> Journey time by car from Gateshead town centre is approximately five minutes and a further five minutes travel from Newcastle upon Tyne.<ref>Using Gateshead International Stadium as reference points. See {{cite web|url=http://www.simplygo.com/download/publication/42497.52|title=The Loop: Timetable|publisher=[[Go North East]]|date=29 July 2012|accessdate=22 December 2012}}</ref> A footpath runs adjacent to the Felling bypass and the journey by foot from Gateshead town centre takes some fifteen minutes. A journey east to [[Heworth Interchange]] also takes around fifteen minutes. Two designated cycle routes run past the stadium. These are [[National Cycle Route 72|Hadrian's Way]], which provides access from [[Tynemouth]] in the east and [[Wylam]] in the west, and the [[National Cycle Route 14|Keelman's Way]], which runs along the south bank of the [[River Tyne]] towards [[Blaydon-on-Tyne]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gateshead.ac.uk/media/15274/academy_for_sport_travel_guide.pdf|title=How to get to the Academy for Sport at Gateshead International Stadium|publisher=[[Gateshead College]]|year=2012|accessdate=26 September 2012}} at p.1</ref>\n\nThe stadium is well served by public transport. It has its own [[Tyne and Wear Metro]] station, the [[Gateshead Stadium Metro station]]. This is at Shelley Drive, some five minutes' walk from the ground.<ref name=\"sport2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gateshead.ac.uk/media/15274/academy_for_sport_travel_guide.pdf|title=How to get to the Academy for Sport at Gateshead International Stadium|publisher=[[Gateshead College]]|year=2012|accessdate=26 September 2012}} at p.2</ref> Trains run direct from this station to all other Metro destinations; trains to [[South Shields Metro station|South Shields]] and [[South Hylton metro station|South Hylton]] stop at platform one while trains travelling towards [[St James Metro station|St James]] and [[Airport Metro station (Tyne and Wear)|Airport]] stop at platform two.<ref name=\"metro\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nexus.org.uk/metro/timetables/gateshead-stadium |title=Metro Stations: Gateshead Stadium |publisher=[[Tyne and Wear Passenger Transport Executive]] |date=July 2012 |accessdate=22 December 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100617165914/http://www.nexus.org.uk/metro/timetables/gateshead-stadium |archivedate=17 June 2010 }}</ref> The Gateshead Stadium Metro station is open seven days a week<ref name=\"metro\"/> and at peak times seventeen trains per hour stop there.<ref name=\"sport2\"/> The nearest mainline railway station is [[Newcastle railway station|Newcastle Central Station]], around {{convert|3|mi|km|0}} away, though local rail travel calls at Heworth Interchange.<ref name=\"sport2\"/> [[Go North East]] operate the 93/4 \"Loop\" bus service, which provides access to the stadium from the [[Team Valley]], [[Gateshead Interchange]], Heworth Interchange and [[Queen Elizabeth Hospital, Gateshead|Queen Elizabeth Hospital]] in [[Sheriff Hill]]. This bus runs every fifteen minutes during the day and every half-hour during evenings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.simplygo.com/download/publication/5870.28|title=Route Map: Loop|publisher=[[Go North East]]|year=2012|accessdate=26 September 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=nb}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2016}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{Commons category|Gateshead Stadium}}\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://online.gateshead.gov.uk/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-26070/Item+15a+-+Gateshead+International+Stadium+%28GIS%29+%E2%80%93+Revised+Draft+Development+Brief.pdf|title=Report to Cabinet &ndash; Gateshead International Stadium &ndash; Draft Development Brief|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111002120533/http://online.gateshead.gov.uk/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-26070/Item+15a+-+Gateshead+International+Stadium+(GIS)+%E2%80%93+Revised+Draft+Development+Brief.pdf|archivedate=2 October 2011|publisher=Gateshead MBC|date=25 May 2010|accessdate=28 December 2012}}\n*{{cite book |title=File on Felling|first=Joan |last=Hewitt |publisher=Gateshead Central Library |year=1990}}\n*{{cite book |title=A Topographical Dictionary of England|url=https://archive.org/details/topographicaldic00lewi2|first=Samuel |last=Lewis|publisher=Lewis|year=1848}}\n*{{cite book |title=Top distance runners of the Century|first=Seppo |last=Luhtala|publisher=Mayer & Mayer Verlag|year=2002}}\n*{{cite book |title=Paralympian, My Autobiography|first=Stephen |last=Miller|publisher=Tonto Books|year=2008}}\n*{{cite book |title=Urban Regeneration|first=Thomas|last=Telford|publisher=The Institute of Civil Engineers|year=1988}}\n*{{cite book |title=The Brewing Grade Review |last=Unknown |publisher=Brewers' Society, London|year=1961}} \n*{{cite book |title=The Tina Turner Experience|first=Chris |last=Welch |publisher=Virgin |year=1995}}\n{{refend}}\n{{Gateshead F.C.}}\n{{Conference National Venues}}\n{{1995 RLWC Venues}}\n{{2000 RLWC Venues}}\n{{featured article}}\n\n[[Category:Athletics (track and field) venues in England]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Gateshead]]\n[[Category:Football venues in England]]\n[[Category:Gateshead F.C.]]\n[[Category:Gateshead A.F.C.]]\n[[Category:Gateshead United F.C.]]\n[[Category:Rugby league stadiums in England]]\n[[Category:Rugby League World Cup stadiums]]\n[[Category:Sports venues in Tyne and Wear]]\n[[Category:Sports venues completed in 1955]]\n[[Category:Sport in Gateshead]]\n[[Category:1955 establishments in the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "AlanBadger22", "label": "safe", "comment": "Tenant Gateshead AFC changed from only 1973 to 1971-1973", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gateshead_International_Stadium"}
{"title_page": "Caitlin Kalinowski", "text_new": "{{short description|American product designer, mechanical engineer}}\n'''Caitlin Kalinowski''' is an American [[product design]]er and [[Mechanical engineering|mechanical engineer]]. She is the head of hardware at [[virtual reality]] technology company [[Oculus VR]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mindtheproduct.com/2017/09/craft-prototyping-caitlin-kalinowski/|title=The Craft of Prototyping by Caitlin Kalinowski|website=mindtheproduct.com|access-date=2018-06-18}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nCaitlin Kalinowski grew up in [[New Hampshire]]. She moved to the west coast, and began attending [[Stanford University]] to study product design. Her parents were both professors.<ref>{{Citation|title=Oculus Connect 2: Shipping Hardware: The Evolution of the Rift|date=2015-11-04|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wml-yZqnQ8U}}</ref> She lives in [[San Francisco]], California.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://lesbianswhotech.org/speakers/caitlin-kalinowski/|title=Caitlin Kalinowski|last=|first=|date=|website=Lesbians Who Tech|publisher=|access-date=2016-10-09}}</ref>\n\nKalinowski is involved with various women's and lesbians' technology groups focused on increasing awareness and resources for women in the technology fields. She is on the board of wogrammer, a project focused on sharing interviews of women engineers, and the advisory board of [[Lesbians Who Tech]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Career ==\nAfter three years at Stanford University, Kalinowski left to begin working at [[OQO]], where she worked on the [[OQO Model 02|OQO model 02]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mindtheproduct.com/2017/09/craft-prototyping-caitlin-kalinowski/|title=The Craft of Prototyping by Caitlin Kalinowski - Mind the Product|date=2017-09-15|work=Mind the Product|access-date=2018-11-29|language=en-GB}}</ref> She later left OQO for [[Apple Inc.|Apple]], where she worked as a technical lead on the design of laptops in the [[MacBook]] product line.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.abacwomen.com/2016/01/522/|title=The woman who heads product design at Oculus|last=Brown|first=Richard|date=2016-01-07|website=ABAC Women's Forum|access-date=2016-10-04}}</ref> While continuing to work half-time at Apple, she returned to Stanford and in 2007 received her bachelor's degree in mechanical engineering. She left Apple to work at Facebook, where she worked on the [[Facebook Bluetooth Beacon]] project.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://firstround.com/review/six-steps-to-superior-product-prototyping-lessons-from-an-apple-and-oculus-engineer/|title=Six Steps to Superior Product Prototyping: Lessons from an Apple and Oculus Engineer\n|website=firstround.com|access-date=2018-06-18}}</ref> After Facebook acquired Oculus VR, Kalinowski joined the company as the head of product design. In 2018 she became the acting head of hardware for Oculus, where she works on the Oculus Go, Santa Cruz prototype, [[Oculus Rift]] and the other virtual reality products developed by the company.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/ladies-storm-hackathons/caitlin-kalinowski-head-of-product-design-oculus-vr-c3fbf27986bf#.he75mkye8|title=Caitlin Kalinowski|last=|first=|date=2015-08-17|website=|publisher=wogrammer|access-date=2016-10-09}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018 she was listed as one of the most powerful female engineers by ''[[Business Insider]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/the-most-powerful-female-engineers-of-2018-2018-4#no-35-sylvia-acevedo-ceo-girl-scouts-5|title=The 39 most powerful female engineers of 2018|last1=Bort|first1=Julia|work=[[Business Insider]]|accessdate=21 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nShe was a featured speaker at WISMP Summit 2018, held in San Francisco on February 3, 2018.<ref>{{cite web |title=WISMP Summit 2018  Saturday, February 3rd in San Francisco |url=https://www.wismp.org/summit/ |accessdate=21 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}} HElO.\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kalinowski, Caitlin}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Facebook employees]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from New Hampshire]]\n[[Category:Lesbians]]\n[[Category:Stanford University alumni]]\n[[Category:American mechanical engineers]]\n[[Category:Apple Inc. employees]]\n[[Category:American women engineers]]\n[[Category:Engineers from New Hampshire]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American product designer, mechanical engineer}}\n'''Caitlin Kalinowski''' is an American [[product design]]er and [[Mechanical engineering|mechanical engineer]]. She is the head of hardware at [[virtual reality]] technology company [[Oculus VR]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mindtheproduct.com/2017/09/craft-prototyping-caitlin-kalinowski/|title=The Craft of Prototyping by Caitlin Kalinowski|website=mindtheproduct.com|access-date=2018-06-18}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nCaitlin Kalinowski grew up in [[New Hampshire]]. She moved to the west coast, and began attending [[Stanford University]] to study product design. Her parents were both professors.<ref>{{Citation|title=Oculus Connect 2: Shipping Hardware: The Evolution of the Rift|date=2015-11-04|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wml-yZqnQ8U}}</ref> She lives in [[San Francisco]], California.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://lesbianswhotech.org/speakers/caitlin-kalinowski/|title=Caitlin Kalinowski|last=|first=|date=|website=Lesbians Who Tech|publisher=|access-date=2016-10-09}}</ref>\n\nKalinowski is involved with various women's and lesbians' technology groups focused on increasing awareness and resources for women in the technology fields. She is on the board of wogrammer, a project focused on sharing interviews of women engineers, and the advisory board of [[Lesbians Who Tech]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Career ==\nAfter three years at Stanford University, Kalinowski left to begin working at [[OQO]], where she worked on the [[OQO Model 02|OQO model 02]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mindtheproduct.com/2017/09/craft-prototyping-caitlin-kalinowski/|title=The Craft of Prototyping by Caitlin Kalinowski - Mind the Product|date=2017-09-15|work=Mind the Product|access-date=2018-11-29|language=en-GB}}</ref> She later left OQO for [[Apple Inc.|Apple]], where she worked as a technical lead on the design of laptops in the [[MacBook]] product line.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.abacwomen.com/2016/01/522/|title=The woman who heads product design at Oculus|last=Brown|first=Richard|date=2016-01-07|website=ABAC Women's Forum|access-date=2016-10-04}}</ref> While continuing to work half-time at Apple, she returned to Stanford and in 2007 received her bachelor's degree in mechanical engineering. She left Apple to work at Facebook, where she worked on the [[Facebook Bluetooth Beacon]] project.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://firstround.com/review/six-steps-to-superior-product-prototyping-lessons-from-an-apple-and-oculus-engineer/|title=Six Steps to Superior Product Prototyping: Lessons from an Apple and Oculus Engineer\n|website=firstround.com|access-date=2018-06-18}}</ref> After Facebook acquired Oculus VR, Kalinowski joined the company as the head of product design. In 2018 she became the acting head of hardware for Oculus, where she works on the Oculus Go, Santa Cruz prototype, [[Oculus Rift]] and the other virtual reality products developed by the company.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/ladies-storm-hackathons/caitlin-kalinowski-head-of-product-design-oculus-vr-c3fbf27986bf#.he75mkye8|title=Caitlin Kalinowski|last=|first=|date=2015-08-17|website=|publisher=wogrammer|access-date=2016-10-09}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018 she was listed as one of the most powerful female engineers by ''[[Business Insider]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/the-most-powerful-female-engineers-of-2018-2018-4#no-35-sylvia-acevedo-ceo-girl-scouts-5|title=The 39 most powerful female engineers of 2018|last1=Bort|first1=Julia|work=[[Business Insider]]|accessdate=21 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nShe was a featured speaker at WISMP Summit 2018, held in San Francisco on February 3, 2018.<ref>{{cite web |title=WISMP Summit 2018  Saturday, February 3rd in San Francisco |url=https://www.wismp.org/summit/ |accessdate=21 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kalinowski, Caitlin}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Facebook employees]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from New Hampshire]]\n[[Category:Lesbians]]\n[[Category:Stanford University alumni]]\n[[Category:American mechanical engineers]]\n[[Category:Apple Inc. employees]]\n[[Category:American women engineers]]\n[[Category:Engineers from New Hampshire]]\n", "name_user": "2600:6c50:280:46ac:31f0:9eaa:f13:3d76", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Caitlin_Kalinowski"}
{"title_page": "List of Old Bedford Modernians", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikimedia list article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2015}}\n[[File:Harpur Window.jpg|thumb|right|200px|The Harpur Window, [[Bedford Modern School]]. ''They Shall Mount Up With Wings As Eagles'']]\n\nThe following is a list of some notable '''Old Bedford Modernians''' who are former pupils of [[Bedford Modern School]] in [[Bedford]], England.  At the school, alumni are known as '''OBMs'''.<ref name=\"auto3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bedmod.co.uk/obms/|title=OBMs|website=Bedford Modern School}}</ref>  The Old Bedford Modernians' Club was founded in 1892.<ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n\n==Academic and educational==\n[[File:William A. Tilden by Harry H. Salomon.jpg|thumb|115px|right|[[William A. Tilden|Sir William Tilden FRS]]]]\n[[File:John Holland Rose.jpg|thumb|115px|right|[[John Holland Rose|Prof. John Holland Rose FBA]]]]\n[[File:Sir Peter Knight and Dr Andrew Miller (7985176466).jpg|thumb|115px|right|[[Peter Knight (scientist)|Sir Peter Knight FRS]]]]\n[[File:Peter Wothers portrait by Nathan Pitt.jpg|thumb|115px|right|[[Peter Wothers|Dr. Peter Wothers MBE]]]]\n* [[William Augustus Tilden|Sir William Augustus Tilden]] [[Royal Society|FRS]] (1842\u20131926), Chemist & Dean, [[Royal College of Science]], London<ref name=\"Underwood 1981\">{{Cite book|title=Bedford Modern School of the black & red|work=worldcat.org|isbn=9780950760803|year=1981|oclc = 16558393}}</ref>\n* [[Joseph Reynolds Green|Professor Joseph Reynolds Green]] [[Royal Society|FRS]] (1848\u20131914), Professor of Botany to the [[Pharmaceutical Society of Great Britain]]<ref>''The Eagle'', The Magazine of [[Bedford Modern School]], Vol. III (1888), p. 243</ref><ref>''The Eagle'' Vol. XXVII, no. 2 (1949), p. 135</ref>\n* [[William Hillhouse|Professor William Hillhouse]] [[Linnean Society of London|FLS]] (1850\u20131910), first Professor of Botany at the [[University of Birmingham]]<ref name=\"Underwood 1981\"/>\n* [[Edward Mann Langley]] (1851\u20131933), founded the [[Mathematical Gazette]], created [[Langley\u2019s Adventitious Angles]]<ref name=\"Underwood 1981\"/>\n* [[William Robert Bousfield]] [[Royal Society|FRS]] (1854\u20131943), [[Physical chemistry|chemist]]<ref name=\"Underwood 1981\"/>\n* [[John Holland Rose|Professor John Holland Rose]] [[Fellow of the British Academy|FBA]] (1855\u20131942), [[Vere Harmsworth Professor of Imperial and Naval History]], [[University of Cambridge]]<ref name=\"Underwood 1981\"/>\n* [[George Charles Crick]] [[Geological Society of London|FGS]] [[Royal Geographical Society|FRGS]] [[Zoological Society of London|FZS]] (1856\u20131917), geologist, authority on [[Cephalopod]]a, 1st Assistant at the [[Natural History Museum, London|Natural History Museum]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nhm.ac.uk/research-curation/library/archives/catalogue/dserve.exe?dsqServer=placid&dsqIni=Dserve.ini&dsqApp=Archive&dsqDb=Persons&dsqSearch=Code==%27PX174%27&dsqCmd=Show.tcl|title=Natural History Museum Archive Catalogue|work=nhm.ac.uk|accessdate=29 April 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Arthur John Pressland]] [[Royal Society of Edinburgh|FRSE]] (1865 \u20131934), educational theorist, linguist, schoolmaster and writer<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Harpur Trust, 1552-1973.|publisher=|isbn=9780950291703|year=1973|oclc = 903515}}</ref>\n* [[George James Gibbs]] [[Royal Astronomical Society|FRAS]] (1866\u20131947), astronomer, engineer, inventor and public science lecturer<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1093/mnras/109.1.1 |title=Meeting of 1949 January 14 |journal=Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society |volume=109 |pages=1\u20132 |year=1949 |last1=Greaves |first1=W. M. H. }}</ref>\n* [[Richard John Durley|Professor Richard John Durley]] [[Order of the British Empire|MBE]] (1868\u20131948), Professor of Mechanical Engineering at [[McGill University]] (1901\u201312)<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1680/IJOTI.1948.13374 |title=Obituary. Richard John Durley, 1868-1948 |journal=Journal of the Institution of Civil Engineers |volume=31 |issue=2 |pages=183 |year=1948 }}</ref>\n* [[Laxton Brothers|Edward Augustine Lowe Laxton]] [[Order of the British Empire|MBE]] (1869\u20131951), expert on fruit production (''[[Laxton's Superb]]'')<ref name=\"Underwood 1981\"/>\n* [[Professor Henry Payne]] [[Royal Aeronautical Society|FRAeS]] [[Institution of Civil Engineers|M.Inst.C.E.]] (1871\u20131945), Professor of Engineering at the [[University of Melbourne]]<ref>{{Cite book|chapter-url=http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/payne-henry-7989|title=Biography \u2013 Henry Payne \u2013 Australian Dictionary of Biography|work=anu.edu.au|accessdate=29 January 2015|chapter=Payne, Henry (1871\u20131945)|publisher=National Centre of Biography, Australian National University}}</ref>\n* [[Jannion Steele Elliott]] (1871\u20131942), [[ornithology|ornithologist]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britishbirds.co.uk/article/obituary-jannion-steele-elliott-1871-1942/|title=Obituary: Jannion Steele Elliott (1871\u20131942)|work=British Birds|accessdate=29 January 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Eric Temple Bell|Dr Eric Temple Bell]], (1883\u20131960), mathematician who specialised in [[number theory]] and formulated the [[Bell series]]<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=aoctKmbvtMYC&pg=PA354&lpg=PA354&dq=edward+mann+langley+alumni#v=onepage&q=edward%20mann%20langley%20alumni|title=The Search for E. T. Bell|accessdate=29 January 2015|isbn=9780883855089|year=1993|last1=Reid|first1=Constance}}</ref>\n* [[Charles Oatley|Sir Charles Oatley]] [[Order of the British Empire|OBE]], [[Royal Society|FRS]] [[FREng]] (1904\u20131996), pioneered the development of the [[scanning electron microscope]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/obituary-professor-sir-charles-oatley-1343206.html|title=Obituary: Professor Sir Charles Oatley|work=The Independent|accessdate=29 January 2015|date=1996-03-21}}</ref>\n* [[Gerald Dunning|Dr. G.C. Dunning]], [[Doctor of Letters|D.Lit]], [[Fellow of the Society of Antiquaries of London|FSA]] (1905\u20131978), pioneering medieval archaeologist, authority on Anglo-Saxon and medieval ceramics<ref>Obituary in ''[[The Times]]'', ''Dr. G.C. Dunning'', ''Work on Medieval Pottery'', 28 April 1978, p.18</ref><ref>A.Underwood, ''School of the Black and Red. A history of Bedford Modern School'' (Bedford, 2010 edn.), p. 130</ref>\n* [[William Francis Grimes|Professor William Francis Grimes]] [[Order of the British Empire|CBE]] (1905\u20131988), Professor of Archaeology, [[University of London]] (1956\u20131973)<ref name=\"Underwood 1981\"/>\n* [[Francis MacCarthy Willis Bund|Reverend Francis MacCarthy Willis Bund]] (1906\u20131980), Chaplain, [[Dean (education)|Dean]] and [[Fellow]] of [[Balliol College, Oxford]]<ref>A. Underwood ''The School of the Black and Red''(Bedord, 2010 edn.) p. 284</ref>\n* [[D. C. Riddy|Dr D. C. Riddy]] [[Order of the British Empire|CBE]] (1907\u20131979), Controller-General of the Education Branch, [[Allied Commission|Control Commission for German \u2013 British Element]]<ref name=\"Underwood 1981\"/>\n* [[F.G. Emmison]] [[Order of the British Empire|MBE]] [[Society of Antiquaries of London|FSA]] [[Historical Society|FRHistS]] (1907\u20131995), archivist, author and historian<ref name=\"Underwood 1981\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/index/60/101060381/|title=Frederick Emmison|work=oxforddnb.com|accessdate=29 May 2015}}</ref>\n* [[J.P.C. Roach|Professor John Roach]] (1920 \u2013 2015), historian<ref name=\"google.co.uk\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=eNo9AAAAYAAJ&dq=educated+bedford+modern+school+new+college+oxford&q=Bedford|title=Essays to a young teacher|year=1966|last1=Howat|first1=Gerald Malcolm David}}</ref>\n* [[Ramsay Shearman|Professor Ramsay Shearman]] DSc [[Fellow of the Royal Academy of Engineering|FReng]] [[Fellow of the Institution of Engineering and Technology|FIET]] [[Royal Meteorological Society|FRMetS]] [[Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers|FIEEE]] (1924-2019), pioneer in shortwave radio and radar<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/ramsay-shearman-obituary-98llh6w0j|title=Ramsay Shearman obituary|via=www.thetimes.co.uk}}</ref>\n* [[Brian Gl\u00fcss|Professor Brian Gl\u00fcss]] [[Royal Statistical Society|FRSS]] (1930\u20132013), statistician, mathematician, systems engineer, author and expert on [[survivor guilt]]<ref>Obituary, ''Dr Brian Gl\u00fcss'', ''Eagle News'', The Magazine of the [[Bedford Modern School|Old Bedford Modernians' Club]], New Series, Volume 6, Number 3 (Issue 110), January 2015</ref>\n* [[John Richard Anthony Pearson|Professor John Richard Anthony Pearson]] [[Royal Society|FRS]] [[Institute of Materials, Minerals and Mining|FIMMM]] [[Institution of Chemical Engineers|MIChemE]] (born 1930), pioneer in [[fluid mechanics]]<ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite web|url=https://global.oup.com/academic/product/whos-who-and-who-was-who-9780199540891?cc=mt&lang=en&|title=Who's Who and Who Was Who: For autobiographical information on the noteworthy & famous.|publisher=Oxford University Press|via=Oxford University Press}}</ref>\n* [[D.J. Bartholomew|Professor David John Bartholomew]] [[Fellow of the British Academy|FBA]] (1931-2017), Professor of Statistics at the [[London School of Economics|LSE]] (1973\u201396)<ref name=\"Underwood 2010\">''School of the Black And Red'' by Andrew Underwood 1981. Reset and updated by Peter Boon, Paul Middleton and Richard Wildman in 2010</ref>\n* [[Philip Bean|Professor Philip Bean]] (born 1936), Professor of [[Criminology]] at [[Loughborough University]], former President of the [[British Society of Criminology|British Soc. of Criminology]]<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n* [[George Richard Pickett|Professor George Richard Pickett]] [[Royal Society|FRS]] (born 1939), Professor of [[Cryogenics|Low Temperature Physics]] at [[Lancaster University]]<ref name=\"Underwood 2010\"/>\n* [[Sid Gray|Professor Sid Gray]] PhD [[FASSA]] [[Chartered Certified Accountan